WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Like good afternoon, this is David Cline for the Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I work in the History Department at Virginia Tech and have the honor of working with the Civil Rights History Project of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Today is June 28, 2016, and I'm in San Diego, California.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:44.000
This project is also co-sponsored by the Southern Oral History Program at UNC Chapel Hill and, as I said, by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Today we have with us Guha Shankar is in the room, behind the camera is John Bishop of Media Generation.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
We have the distinct honor to be visiting with Harold Brown here in San Diego.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And this is the one time that I will coach you at all is just if you could start with a complete sentence, then we'll just go into conversation.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:12.000
But my name is, or I am, and your name and the year of your birth and where you're born.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:20.000
My name is Harold K. Brown known, better known as Hal Brown.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:33.000
I was born in York, Pennsylvania, and migrated to San Diego through San Diego State University in 1953.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.000
And you were born when?

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:51.000
I was born in 1934, and I am the son of Mrs. Emma Brown, and I am one of seven siblings.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And could we start with your childhood? You said you were born in Pennsylvania, but if you could tell us a little bit about what you're up bringing with like and who your people were.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:19.000
I like to start by saying that, you know, I'm trying to answer the question is what breeds a civil rights activist or a civil rights militant as we were called in the 60s.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So I grew up in a community, mostly farm community of approximately 1% or less black citizens.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:45.000
And your Pennsylvania was typical of the United States of America at that time.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
There was segregated housing.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:56.000
So I grew up in a segregated, what was called in those days a colored community.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:10.000
And we were all rather poor, not poor to the extent that we didn't have food and we didn't have clothing.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:22.000
But we were all in pretty much the same boat. It was a group of people who had very few opportunities, if any.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:30.000
We lived there, we went to segregated schools up until the seventh grade is when we integrated.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And so jobs were scarce for our families and so income was very, very low.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.000
So that's the environment I grew up in.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:54.000
And there are parts of Pennsylvania, I feel like a lot of people don't know this, that we're really, really rough.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Absolutely. Absolutely. People don't think of the north. People from the south don't think of the north as being a tough place to live for black people descending some slave.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:29.000
But it was. And when people moved from when blacks moved from the south to the north, they found that there was a lot of hardship there in terms of segregated housing and discriminated employment.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And so that's what I grew up in and faced a lot of insults. One of the stories I tell is that I caught my introduction really to racism in America.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And that was when I was in elementary school, we had to go to a black and quotes elementary school.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And when we would walk all somewhere around maybe five miles to the school, pass white schools to get there.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:17.000
And there was a chain works factory on en route to our school.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:34.000
And the men used to hang out the windows on the upper floors and just hurl all kinds of racial insults, calling us names all the whole time.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And it just happened every day. And so that was my introduction at age six.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And your children and those are adults. Yes, just children.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:06:05.000
So hindsight helps us in these things. Looking back, can you start to see where a race consciousness of some kind started to form for you?

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Absolutely. I joke about it when I tell people that when I was born and came out of the womb, I saw the doctor and some nurses and they were all white.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:31.000
And so I didn't know I was black until my mother took me home to this colored community.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:40.000
And then I began to look around and I saw, you know, these people were different colors than once I saw when I came into this world.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:52.000
But that was sort of the introduction that I like to talk about because it illustrates that there was a difference right from the beginning.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And I attribute the psychological and mental exposure to this which had its impact right from the beginning.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:27.000
And the names and the insults and the observation of no blacks being in positions of importance in the city, all of them were whites and mostly white males.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:39.000
And so this I attribute to the learning in America of a young black kid growing up.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:08:00.000
And so there was just a building on that, you know, from going from a segregated elementary school to an integrated junior high school and the impact that that had the difference.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:28.000
And I suspect it must have had an impact on the white students as well. But that being the only black in a classroom and experiencing the officers of the school, the teachers of the school, the administrators of the school, you know, there's all, you're in a white world.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And here you are being the victim of insults that come and everything that you see just about substantiates the fact that you are less than the rest of them.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And that builds into the mind of a child. And I guess leads to the point where the psychological tests where black kids say select a white kid is being the good kid and the smart kid as opposed to selecting a black kid.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:23.000
Now, were there any forces that you can remember whether at home or in the school or elsewhere that were pushing against that for you that were giving you a different message, a message about black pride?

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:42.000
Well, the one that I cite the most is that the contradiction takes place when I entered junior high school.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:10:02.000
My home-room teacher, Cassandra Shea, just sort of adopted me and she was a white math teacher and my home-room teacher. But she introduced me the concept of college, which I didn't know anything about, never heard of.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:26.000
She introduced me to that and explained that out of the blue that you want to think about going to college, Harold, and she explained how she had, she went to college and her family wasn't, didn't have the financial ability to put her to college.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:51.000
She got a job and she worked through college like cleaning people's home houses and so forth. And so, you know, there here was a, where's a, made an impression on me. And then when my football coach there in junior high school says to me, how, you know, you ought to be a dentist.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:11:09.000
And I go, you know, dentists. I mean, that was farthest from me. I never knew a dentist, never saw anybody, you know, a black professional just was not heard. We had a few black teachers who taught in black schools.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:31.000
But to have a black person in the community as a dentist or a doctor and so forth, we had one black doctor and no black dentist. But that coach of mine introduced me to some things that I had not even thought about.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:57.000
So, you know, there's this, this, this, now this contradiction begins to build in is that, you know, here, here is all this white world and that's bad. But then here's some people who are the same color, but who have shown a great amount of love and acceptance and encouragement and so forth.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:16.000
And, you know, I just think a young people growing up, that's a lot to deal with. The mind is young and being developed and when you have these kinds of things which are really unnecessary.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:31.000
So, I credit our, the forefathers of this country for not looking into the future for enough to prevent all this stuff.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:42.000
During your schooling then, and into high school, was there any black history at all that was taught or no?

00:12:42.000 --> 00:13:01.000
In fact, I can remember and as I used to go back to Pennsylvania on vacation and talk with my friends who I grew up with, went to school.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:30.000
And our black friends used to laugh about this because the only thing that we saw interracially was slaves pictured and when that would happen, when they would show those pictures and everything that these blacks in the cotton fields picking cotton and everything.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And then, we as blacks would scringe down in our seats and try to, try to disappear from, and then of course we found the humor in it as we became adults and we would laugh about it.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And then there was another example of, of non history, non black history teaching, there was our music teacher there during your high school would always, somehow find the song Old Black Joe".

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:17.000
And she would play that, it seems like every class that we had every day.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:22.160
She would play this thing and she would sit at the piano and we would all have to sing.

00:14:22.160 --> 00:14:32.320
Now remember, you're the only black or maybe a couple in the class of all whites.

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:40.100
And when you did that, you know, black students, like guests, which is grabbed their chairs

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:49.160
tightly and kind of get down and hope that they could just disappear and get through this.

00:14:49.160 --> 00:14:53.120
And again, as adults, we laugh about it.

00:14:53.120 --> 00:15:09.440
So no, I didn't learn anything about black history until I graduated from college.

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:18.560
And that's when I began on my own to read and learn about the history of black folks in

00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:19.560
America.

00:15:20.560 --> 00:15:25.560
So can you tell me a little bit about your journey toward college?

00:15:25.560 --> 00:15:29.560
You were an athlete in high school and that was part of what brought you to San Diego.

00:15:29.560 --> 00:15:30.560
Yes.

00:15:30.560 --> 00:15:31.560
Can you tell us a little bit about that?

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:35.320
That was really what brought me to San Diego.

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:45.680
And I started out as a basketball and baseball player since elementary school.

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:52.400
And I was in high school.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:59.040
I became quite popular as a sort of an accomplished athlete.

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:10.400
I was selected as the all-state basketball player in my senior year and followed in my brother's

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:16.840
foot steps because he had also achieved that as the first basketball player in the history

00:16:16.840 --> 00:16:23.280
of our school to achieve that status of all-state status.

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:25.280
And I was a second.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:39.200
So I was very popular as athletes are in junior high school and in high school.

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:46.480
And I was a baseball player, as I mentioned, in addition to basketball.

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:58.760
I wasn't tall enough to receive any real attention to be recruited to these colleges and so

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:00.000
forth.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:07.560
But two people who had attended San Diego State, older fellows who were in the Navy and

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:15.760
they had been to San Diego and actually ended up playing basketball for San Diego State.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:23.680
And as I came along in my senior year, when they came home to York, they approached me and

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:26.000
encouraged me to go there.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:35.560
Well, my counselors had already sort of programmed me to go to Penn State, which I did.

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:44.480
And I attended Penn State on a scholarship, on a basketball scholarship, which paid for

00:17:44.480 --> 00:17:47.840
my tuition, but that was about it.

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:59.400
And there was no money for rent or food or anything like that.

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:11.480
So I eventually left there and went to accept a trial with the St. Louis Browns in Thomasville,

00:18:11.480 --> 00:18:13.280
Georgia.

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:15.040
And I did that.

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:22.840
And after a couple of injuries, I went back home to York and wrote the coach at San Diego

00:18:22.840 --> 00:18:27.080
State and said that I was ready to come out there.

00:18:27.080 --> 00:18:37.640
And so I did that and I came to San Diego and was because I was a transfer, I was in

00:18:37.640 --> 00:18:39.640
Eligible to play.

00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:41.320
I had to wait out a year.

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:45.720
So the coach at San Diego State told me, he said, how would you do that?

00:18:45.720 --> 00:18:53.160
I have you go to the junior college first and just, you won't miss your education, but

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:58.280
you won't be able to play at San Diego State, but you can play there and it won't be counted

00:18:58.280 --> 00:19:00.280
against your eligibility.

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:03.000
I saw, that sounds like a good plan.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:10.840
Well, it was not correct because when I went there and signed up for the classes and

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:15.480
so forth, and then to junior college, it would have counted.

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:25.260
So I didn't play until I got to San Diego State and I was in between junior college and

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:26.340
San Diego State.

00:19:26.340 --> 00:19:29.000
I was drafted into the Army.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:39.720
And so I spent two years in the Army and then I went to San Diego State.

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:43.040
So did you end up playing for the St. Louis Browns?

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:44.040
No.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:48.440
I did not.

00:19:48.440 --> 00:19:55.720
One of the things that I talk about and I try to help with younger people is making sure

00:19:55.720 --> 00:20:05.720
that they have someone in their lives who can provide some guidance and advice.

00:20:05.720 --> 00:20:21.840
I grew up with a mother and some older siblings, but there wasn't any person in my life other

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:22.840
than in school.

00:20:22.840 --> 00:20:29.840
It wasn't any person who really provides this advice and guidance and so on and introduced

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:33.760
me to things that I should be introduced to.

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:42.400
So when I went to an example of this is when I went to the minor league training for the

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:51.680
St. Louis Browns, I went there not knowing that you are expected when you arrive to be

00:20:51.680 --> 00:20:54.600
in shape and ready to play ball.

00:20:54.600 --> 00:21:04.760
Well my experience was that in York, Pennsylvania, it was cold in the winter and you might get

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:14.160
your glove and ball and start throwing a little bit in the gym, come April and do some running

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:15.160
a little bit.

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:17.880
So when I got there, I was shocked.

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:26.520
I mean, we were going full steam, running wind, windspinths and throwing hard and feeling

00:21:26.520 --> 00:21:35.960
and all this stuff and my arm couldn't take it, my legs couldn't take it and so I was playing.

00:21:35.960 --> 00:21:43.600
I was a shortstop and I was trying to throw from short to first and needles and things

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:46.480
just felt like all through my arms.

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:49.400
So that was a bad try.

00:21:49.400 --> 00:22:02.000
I had to go home and then I just waited my time to throw the next step which was my next

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:03.400
step was okay.

00:22:03.400 --> 00:22:11.200
I went back in the college because I wanted to play ball in college and that's what happened.

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:13.240
Ended up at San Diego State.

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:21.520
Let me ask you, I want to ask about your military service but just a question about racial dynamics

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:24.560
on teams and in the locker room.

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:27.960
Was that a different situation or more of the same?

00:22:27.960 --> 00:22:31.360
Can you tell us a little bit about what your experiences were there?

00:22:31.360 --> 00:22:43.320
I think sports is such a great opportunity to address the racial issue.

00:22:43.320 --> 00:22:53.920
Some of the friends that I really got to have growing up through sports and maybe there

00:22:53.920 --> 00:23:01.520
were a couple or so other white students who I got to be friends with.

00:23:01.520 --> 00:23:13.840
But the ones I really got to know and have some association with beyond the school boundaries

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:25.440
was with those teammates and all through junior high school that was true.

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:28.560
And of course you have the blacks who made the team.

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:34.840
Of course we all lived in the same neighborhoods or close by and we knew each other.

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:42.240
We saw each other after school and we had a separate facility, a separate recreational

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:51.520
facility called Crispus Attucks Center, community center that we blacks went to and so we

00:23:51.520 --> 00:24:02.000
were together but getting relationships with your white classmates and so forth is really

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:03.000
hard.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:12.080
If it were not for the sports program, it probably just would hardly happen at all.

00:24:12.080 --> 00:24:16.560
And that and all went through junior high school.

00:24:16.560 --> 00:24:31.880
In high school it was even more difficult to have relationships with the white students

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:41.520
even the schoolmates, even your teammates because they came from different parts of the

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:47.680
county and you saw them and you played and that was it.

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:50.120
Wasn't like you were going over to each other's houses?

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:51.920
No, nothing I could.

00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:59.120
You didn't get to really know them and they didn't get to know you.

00:24:59.120 --> 00:25:03.600
In college, playing ball in college it was the same thing.

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:18.480
I mean, you have very few blacks on the team and the white players you saw at practice and

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:23.800
maybe in the cafeteria once in a while and that was it.

00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:31.620
The black players, we were together after the practice during the evenings on weekends

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:35.820
sometimes.

00:25:35.820 --> 00:25:47.680
While sports offered a great opportunity, they still left a lot to be desired and I regret

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:55.520
that more was not done during that period when I was an athlete.

00:25:55.520 --> 00:26:01.760
As you were saying before, did you go out to San Diego and then went for the year of junior

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:06.080
college and then the military came calling?

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:10.120
Can you tell us about that?

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:20.200
When I left San Diego, when I left school after junior college for the summer, I went

00:26:20.200 --> 00:26:25.120
back to Pennsylvania and what year was that?

00:26:25.120 --> 00:26:32.880
That was 1953.

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:41.840
When I went back to New York, I inquired about because I didn't want to make a trip back

00:26:41.840 --> 00:26:49.560
to California and then get drafted and then I have to return back to Pennsylvania and be

00:26:49.560 --> 00:26:52.160
inducted from Pennsylvania.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:27:00.960
So I inquired when I was in New York about my status, my draft status and the person told

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:06.840
me, oh, you're right close to being drafted.

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:12.280
Whether that was true or not, I'm not so sure.

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:19.800
But I said, well, I might as well get it going now and get my two years over.

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:21.240
So that's what I did.

00:27:21.240 --> 00:27:26.640
That's right at the end of the Korean War was one heading down.

00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:37.600
Right at the end of the Korean War and I did my training in Georgia.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:42.160
I was going to say Thomas, we're going to get mixed up with my baseball.

00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:47.120
It was with the Camp Gordon.

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:50.480
What was the situation like there at that time?

00:27:51.480 --> 00:27:58.720
As long as you stayed on the base, things were okay mostly.

00:27:58.720 --> 00:28:07.720
It wasn't like there was any, you could mix with males but there wasn't any mixing with

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:11.000
females as a black person.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:20.200
Now the movies, the mess hall and so forth where you ate and all that was fine.

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:21.960
There was no parks.

00:28:21.960 --> 00:28:27.960
As long as you stayed on the post, when you went off post in the town, that's when you ran

00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:29.360
in the trouble.

00:28:29.360 --> 00:28:37.120
That's where I saw signs as we would be walking down the street.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:45.960
You'd see signs saying no, no, no, no, Jews or niggers allowed, no dogs, Jews or niggers

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:47.760
allowed.

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:52.440
You'd see that kind of stuff.

00:28:52.440 --> 00:29:00.320
We limited our contact, we just didn't go into town very much.

00:29:00.320 --> 00:29:02.240
That was my basic training.

00:29:02.240 --> 00:29:14.680
Then I was then sent to New Jersey at Fort Momoth where that was my permanent station there.

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:17.720
How are things in New Jersey?

00:29:17.720 --> 00:29:24.160
New Jersey was fine.

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:36.200
We could go to, after hours, we would go out in the town a little bit and go out to the

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:43.120
school bar and guys would have some drinks and so forth.

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:51.800
We never experienced any problems there except for one.

00:29:51.800 --> 00:30:05.680
I received an assignment to go to Louisiana on an operation called Operation Sagebrush.

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:11.360
I was assigned to that and we were going to.

00:30:11.360 --> 00:30:22.080
What I knew at this point in my life about racism in America, I was not going there.

00:30:22.080 --> 00:30:32.800
So in my naivete decided I was going to the post commander and tell him I'm not going

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:37.160
down there.

00:30:37.160 --> 00:30:39.520
Here I am just an enlisted man.

00:30:39.520 --> 00:30:40.920
I'm not an officer.

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:42.240
I'm an enlisted man.

00:30:42.240 --> 00:30:46.600
Even an officer wouldn't do that.

00:30:46.600 --> 00:30:54.920
I requested, well I went over and just asked to see and talk with him.

00:30:54.920 --> 00:30:59.880
He invited me in and I told him.

00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:10.280
I said, as an e-girl, he just does make any sense for me to go to a place where I'm not

00:31:10.280 --> 00:31:19.640
wanted and to have to go to the south and be exposed to those conditions.

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:22.280
I'm sure I didn't say it in these words.

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:33.760
I was a young shy kid who was just upset and because I'm afraid I guess.

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:42.360
He looked at me and he listened and he said something.

00:31:42.360 --> 00:31:49.640
He returned to your barracks.

00:31:49.640 --> 00:31:58.940
I returned to my barracks and we received orders to ship out and I was among those who

00:31:58.940 --> 00:32:10.320
shipped out along with all the others and we were shipped down to Louisiana and lived in

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:17.720
the outskirts of the town.

00:32:17.720 --> 00:32:22.360
We just stayed out there and going in town.

00:32:22.360 --> 00:32:31.560
I think only went in town one time to Shreveport, Louisiana and didn't experience anything but I certainly

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:36.640
didn't notice any integration or anything like that.

00:32:36.640 --> 00:32:48.440
We did our time down there and shipped back to Fort Mammoth, New Jersey.

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:51.960
So you did your two years and then back to San Diego?

00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:54.960
Yes.

00:32:55.960 --> 00:33:11.120
San Diego State was a good experience but at the same time it's just been one incident

00:33:11.120 --> 00:33:24.520
after another that spoke to you as a descendant of slaves as a black person, as a negro,

00:33:24.520 --> 00:33:26.680
as a colored person.

00:33:26.680 --> 00:33:38.360
It just kept coming incident after incident in a reminder form that you are not a first-class

00:33:38.360 --> 00:33:42.480
citizen in this country.

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:52.800
My experience at San Diego State, one thing that stands out is that while I was an athlete

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:58.880
I was also interested in student government and so forth.

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:04.960
So I was encouraged to run for an office in student government.

00:34:04.960 --> 00:34:05.960
I did.

00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:12.080
I won and set on the council, student council.

00:34:12.080 --> 00:34:18.440
On that council I was asked to chair a certain committee.

00:34:18.440 --> 00:34:21.960
It was called the Constitution's Committee.

00:34:21.960 --> 00:34:33.920
That committee was responsible for reviewing the constitutions and charters of all the on-campus

00:34:33.920 --> 00:34:40.200
organizations, all the sororities, all the fraternities and so on.

00:34:40.200 --> 00:34:54.640
So when I started reviewing these I saw in the charters of the fraternities, of white

00:34:54.640 --> 00:35:06.400
fraternities and sororities that it was for white male or white female and in good conscience

00:35:06.400 --> 00:35:08.440
I couldn't approve that.

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:11.800
And so I didn't approve them.

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:19.000
And of course my recommendation was to be made to the council and then the council would

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:20.000
bow down.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:27.200
Well, of course when I didn't approve them that meant they would not receive on-campus

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:30.800
status and all the privileges thereof.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:40.040
And so of course I was called in by the dean of students and we had a chat about it and

00:35:40.040 --> 00:35:41.560
so forth.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:52.280
And I never found out what actually happened whether or not these people, these organizations

00:35:52.280 --> 00:35:57.960
really received on-campus status or probationary status for some reason.

00:35:57.960 --> 00:36:03.000
And I didn't push it beyond that.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:11.760
And that was my experience that really stood out at San Diego State along with the friendship

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:22.800
and the real guidance and love that I received from some of the faculty members at that time.

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:28.880
So again there was sort of a balancing of that.

00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:40.040
I think there were about 25 black students in the whole university at that time and out

00:36:40.040 --> 00:36:48.800
of an enrollment I think it must have been around the year 7000 something like that.

00:36:48.800 --> 00:36:57.400
And here again you sit in the classroom, you're the only black student.

00:36:57.400 --> 00:37:02.600
And it's the same thing over again.

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:09.280
You know, I mean you didn't run into any, it wasn't that you've had some great incidents.

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:18.760
But still I mean that's, you know, the black status program was created in this country.

00:37:18.760 --> 00:37:30.320
In part to provide some companionship for those of that ethnicity.

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:35.680
And although there was a lot of pushback on that.

00:37:35.680 --> 00:37:45.440
But you know, it's your young, you want companionship and friendship and you need that to grow

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:46.440
and so on.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:48.200
And all students need that.

00:37:48.200 --> 00:37:58.560
But when you sit there in a land of what you know to be racist towards you and when you

00:37:58.560 --> 00:38:06.520
walk down a street and you're called nigger, you're right there in San Diego.

00:38:06.520 --> 00:38:10.920
I mean, you know, I mean that's your life.

00:38:10.920 --> 00:38:21.680
And you end up, you know, I guess with some some some feelings, what those feelings happen

00:38:21.680 --> 00:38:24.720
to be depends on the individual.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:27.880
For me it was anger.

00:38:27.880 --> 00:38:33.280
I was angry and I knew that I had to do something about it.

00:38:33.280 --> 00:38:40.560
I was, but sure, I wasn't in junior high school and I wasn't in high school age.

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:50.360
I had been around a little bit and I mature and the further I went, the more angry I got.

00:38:50.360 --> 00:38:58.440
And so that's how I decided when I graduated from San Diego State to join the civil rights

00:38:58.440 --> 00:38:59.440
movement.

00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:07.400
You got a very small African American community obviously at the school.

00:39:07.400 --> 00:39:10.520
What about within the city of San Diego?

00:39:10.520 --> 00:39:15.800
Yeah, it was always around 6%.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:23.740
And as I recall when we were, when we had formed the Congress of Racial Equality here in

00:39:23.740 --> 00:39:35.160
San Diego, I recall that the number of blacks in San Diego was at some of the things somewhere

00:39:35.160 --> 00:39:40.040
around 60,000.

00:39:40.040 --> 00:39:45.800
And I don't know what the San Diego population was, but that number of 60,000 seemed.

00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:51.320
It was, well, it was around 6% as I recall.

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:55.920
And so you graduated and but stayed in the city.

00:39:55.920 --> 00:39:57.080
What else did you do?

00:39:57.080 --> 00:40:01.160
And you said, I want to hear the story of you turning to the civil rights movement, but

00:40:01.160 --> 00:40:03.960
what did you do post graduation?

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:14.320
Well, I did post graduate work here at San Diego State in speech pathology.

00:40:14.320 --> 00:40:20.200
And I was waiting to see if I could get a job teaching school.

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:32.600
Now here's another thing about where this guidance and counseling for young people is so necessary.

00:40:32.600 --> 00:40:41.640
When I was in junior high school and especially in high school, I wanted to be a physical education

00:40:41.640 --> 00:40:44.520
teacher and a coach.

00:40:44.520 --> 00:40:52.040
That's what I knew and that's where I felt comfortable and that's what I did best.

00:40:52.040 --> 00:41:00.040
I liked school and I was good in school, but I excelled in that area.

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:06.360
So and I went to San Diego State, I accomplished that.

00:41:06.360 --> 00:41:15.560
My major was in physical education and my minor was in speech correction or the speech pathology

00:41:15.560 --> 00:41:17.720
area.

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:20.560
But I wanted to be a coach.

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:29.600
Now, after I graduated, I'm waiting around for a job and it occurs to me.

00:41:29.600 --> 00:41:36.800
Wait a minute, they don't hire blacks to coach in high schools.

00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:46.320
Now here I am, you know, me all these years, I mean, it looks like I would have put two

00:41:46.320 --> 00:41:49.600
and two together through those years.

00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:54.720
But for some reason, when I came to San Diego, I graduated from San Diego State, I thought,

00:41:54.720 --> 00:42:00.280
okay, I'm going toward my goal, I'll be a coach.

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:06.920
But then, bang, they don't hire you.

00:42:06.920 --> 00:42:16.480
And so I tried to get a job just teaching at physical education on the junior high level

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:21.600
or even on the high school level.

00:42:21.600 --> 00:42:28.880
So when I applied for a position, not in the city of San Diego, but this was in the city

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:30.560
of La Mesa, California.

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:31.560
And I applied.

00:42:31.560 --> 00:42:34.520
And they said the only way they could hire me.

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:37.800
And I think this guy was the superintendent.

00:42:37.800 --> 00:42:47.120
Said the only way I could hire me is if they pulled all the teachers in the district

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:54.680
to see if it would be okay to hire a Negro.

00:42:54.680 --> 00:43:01.560
So I said, well, forget that.

00:43:01.560 --> 00:43:15.000
And I just decided that I was approached by an organization that was starting called

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:21.160
the El Cajon Valley Open Housing Committee.

00:43:21.160 --> 00:43:37.600
And they formed to, for the purpose of integrating the neighborhoods in La Mesa, California and El Cajon Valley,

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:40.760
just east of San Diego State.

00:43:40.760 --> 00:43:43.920
And so I joined with them.

00:43:43.920 --> 00:43:46.160
This was an all white group.

00:43:46.160 --> 00:43:49.360
I joined with them.

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:53.880
And then about a year into that.

00:43:53.880 --> 00:44:01.640
So I was approached by a black fellow who happened to be one of those meetings that we held.

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:08.800
And he said that they were forming a chapter of core in San Diego.

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:12.680
And would I join with them?

00:44:12.680 --> 00:44:15.120
And then I did.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:19.400
And I think that was 1960.

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:26.320
And so that started my career in core in that year.

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:32.600
But I did get a job teaching school.

00:44:32.600 --> 00:44:45.480
I received this position as a result of one of my schoolmates at San Diego State who

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:47.480
knew me.

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:50.680
And I think we were maybe in a class together.

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:52.320
And so he knew me.

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:58.000
And they were looking for a teacher there where he was teaching.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:04.160
And he recommended to the principal recommended me.

00:45:04.160 --> 00:45:09.560
And so they got in touch with me and brought me out for an interview.

00:45:09.560 --> 00:45:14.000
And in the meantime, I had no idea that I was going to get a job.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:16.000
I mean, I was kind of sweating it out.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:21.320
We were getting close to September.

00:45:21.320 --> 00:45:24.400
And I didn't have a job.

00:45:24.400 --> 00:45:27.720
So I talked with the principal and everything.

00:45:27.720 --> 00:45:28.720
And they hired me.

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:33.000
And I had a great time teaching there for five years.

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:42.080
And before I went into the Peace Corps, I was invited into the Peace Corps to apply for

00:45:42.080 --> 00:45:47.360
a position as deputy director, which I did.

00:45:47.360 --> 00:45:56.160
And then was assigned to the South Africa, Southern Africa.

00:45:56.160 --> 00:46:04.920
So with the Congress of Racial Quality, did you know much about them already before you

00:46:04.920 --> 00:46:06.760
heard about this in Diego chapter?

00:46:06.760 --> 00:46:07.760
No.

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:12.240
I knew nothing about core.

00:46:12.240 --> 00:46:19.800
So there was a meeting to organize it.

00:46:19.800 --> 00:46:27.600
And I decided because this was my first year of teaching that I better cool it.

00:46:27.600 --> 00:46:33.680
And something told me, look, don't do that your first year.

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:37.520
Let them see what you can do as a teacher.

00:46:38.520 --> 00:46:46.120
Once you get a year under your belt, then you can pursue your activities in the civil

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:47.200
rights movement.

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:49.200
So that's what I did.

00:46:49.200 --> 00:46:58.600
And fortunately, I was selected as one of the five outstanding new teachers in San Diego.

00:46:58.600 --> 00:47:00.760
So I had that under my belt.

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:11.720
And then I decided, OK, I'll go and then I became the chairman of the San Diego Corps.

00:47:11.720 --> 00:47:13.960
And we went straight to chairman.

00:47:13.960 --> 00:47:14.960
Well, yes.

00:47:14.960 --> 00:47:15.960
You didn't mess around.

00:47:15.960 --> 00:47:16.960
No.

00:47:20.960 --> 00:47:23.960
So this is around 1960.

00:47:23.960 --> 00:47:24.960
Correct.

00:47:24.960 --> 00:47:26.960
That was about 61.

00:47:26.960 --> 00:47:27.960
61.

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:37.880
So where were you in say 1955 when the Montgomery bus boycott was going on?

00:47:37.880 --> 00:47:43.160
I had just separated.

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:47.160
No, I was in the, I was still in the army.

00:47:47.160 --> 00:47:53.280
I went in in 54 and I was separated from the army in 56.

00:47:53.280 --> 00:47:58.120
So I was at Fort Monmouth, NJ then.

00:47:58.120 --> 00:47:59.920
And what do you watch in television?

00:47:59.920 --> 00:48:04.840
OK, yeah, I was going to say, would you have gotten newspapers or even black newspapers

00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:05.840
where they allowed on base?

00:48:05.840 --> 00:48:08.240
I know sometimes they weren't.

00:48:08.240 --> 00:48:10.840
That were you following the news?

00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:22.200
I was following the news through television, but never saw a newspaper.

00:48:22.200 --> 00:48:30.400
While I was at Fort Monmouth, NJ, then I would get weekend passes once in a while.

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:39.960
And so I'd go to York and visit my family and of course the papers and the news there.

00:48:39.960 --> 00:48:50.640
But I watched on TV, you know, all the civil rights activities that were going on and

00:48:50.640 --> 00:48:54.640
some basketball.

00:48:54.640 --> 00:48:56.960
OK, so I just wanted to ask that question.

00:48:56.960 --> 00:49:02.400
So back to Corr, then, can you tell me about what that was like, organizing the chapter

00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:09.040
and what you all recognized as the major challenges in the city and what you wanted to focus?

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:10.040
Yes.

00:49:10.040 --> 00:49:21.720
We had a person who I think he was affiliated with National Corr in some way.

00:49:21.720 --> 00:49:29.160
And he helped us form the San Diego chapter.

00:49:29.160 --> 00:49:35.840
And I remember we met and you know, we wrote up the bylaws, et cetera, et cetera, formed

00:49:35.840 --> 00:49:41.280
a 501(c) organization.

00:49:41.280 --> 00:49:55.200
Then as we met and I think we were meeting pretty regularly then, we had elections and so

00:49:55.200 --> 00:49:56.200
forth.

00:49:56.200 --> 00:50:03.960
And they had asked me if I would run for the position of chairman, which I did.

00:50:03.960 --> 00:50:18.680
And there was some problems there because prior to that, I had also become a member of

00:50:18.680 --> 00:50:26.560
an organization which was known as the Black National Disorganization.

00:50:26.560 --> 00:50:30.440
It was the Afro-American Association.

00:50:30.440 --> 00:50:37.560
Now, it was labeled, I think, a Black nationalist organization.

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:42.440
That's what the media and this particular thing called this Black Nationalist.

00:50:42.440 --> 00:50:45.800
I didn't know what that was at first.

00:50:45.800 --> 00:50:56.280
So the purpose of that organization was still there's a need today.

00:50:56.280 --> 00:51:07.440
We formed it to educate Black people about the plight of Black people in America, teaching

00:51:07.440 --> 00:51:15.240
Black history and having discussions and so forth about the conditions of Black folk in

00:51:15.240 --> 00:51:16.800
America.

00:51:16.800 --> 00:51:21.360
And so that was a nice experience, a very good experience.

00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:27.960
So this connects back to what I asked you earlier if you had had Black history in school.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:31.160
And this is a program of self-education.

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:33.360
Yes, absolutely.

00:51:33.360 --> 00:51:44.480
And my first introduction to many of the books that I have in my library now and discussions

00:51:44.480 --> 00:51:49.520
and so forth and I reached a point where I remember, I think the first one I read was

00:51:49.520 --> 00:51:58.720
Lerone Bennett Jr Jr by Lerone Bennett Jr and I had discussions with young people about

00:51:58.720 --> 00:52:00.480
our history.

00:52:00.480 --> 00:52:07.120
And so then when I ran for the position of chairman and became the chairman and the conditions

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:15.760
were deplorable as we found them here in San Diego.

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:23.360
Not only were there segregated schools, but there's I recall there were 19 schools in San

00:52:23.360 --> 00:52:28.120
Diego that were segregated.

00:52:28.120 --> 00:52:41.280
And we found that to be serious, but we found employment discrimination to be really our

00:52:41.280 --> 00:52:43.480
top priority.

00:52:43.480 --> 00:52:56.440
And so we worked on the businesses, the companies around San Diego to try to open up these companies

00:52:56.440 --> 00:52:58.520
to higher blacks.

00:52:58.520 --> 00:53:04.880
Now blacks could not be hired in the grocery stores.

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:06.280
These chain stores and everything.

00:53:06.280 --> 00:53:15.480
They didn't hire blacks even as, with because of those, those, those, baggers.

00:53:15.480 --> 00:53:22.760
Yes, much less than other positions of cashier and imaginary.

00:53:22.760 --> 00:53:25.680
You couldn't even be hired as a bagger.

00:53:25.680 --> 00:53:30.560
And there were no freeways back then.

00:53:30.560 --> 00:53:36.320
So the downtown, there were no blacks who worked in the downtown.

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:44.400
Just prior to some years before I started in core, they had had some demonstrations against

00:53:44.400 --> 00:53:50.000
I think it was Woolworths and because he couldn't sit, he couldn't eat in Woolworths and

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:58.760
it was led by a black dentist, Dr. Kimbrough, who, who, John to Dr. Jack Kimbrough.

00:53:58.760 --> 00:54:06.680
And so, you know, the conditions were, I mean, you couldn't rent, you couldn't, you couldn't

00:54:06.680 --> 00:54:08.560
live.

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:18.680
You couldn't rent or buy a house or apartment outside of what was called Logan Heights.

00:54:18.680 --> 00:54:29.920
Where blacks were forced to live, Logan Heights and now it's known as Southeast and

00:54:29.920 --> 00:54:32.080
Logan Heights.

00:54:32.080 --> 00:54:34.120
So you had to live in that area.

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:45.440
And then I talk about an example of that is when the young lady that I married in 1967,

00:54:45.440 --> 00:54:47.920
she came to San Diego.

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:51.320
She was recruited to San Diego.

00:54:51.320 --> 00:54:57.520
You were just starting to talk about the woman that who you were.

00:54:57.520 --> 00:54:58.520
Oh, you're right.

00:54:58.520 --> 00:55:00.560
Yeah, in 1967.

00:55:00.560 --> 00:55:06.440
She was recruited to come to San Diego with general dynamics.

00:55:06.440 --> 00:55:13.000
She was as a math major who graduated from Alabama State University.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:19.240
She came, she was living in Ohio, Columbus, Ohio at the time.

00:55:19.240 --> 00:55:27.440
She was recruited to come to San Diego to work for general dynamics as a systems programmer,

00:55:27.440 --> 00:55:28.440
computer programmer.

00:55:28.440 --> 00:55:37.080
And so, she accepted and she came here and couldn't find a place to live.

00:55:37.080 --> 00:55:47.400
She was given a list by general dynamics of places to apartments and houses and so forth

00:55:47.400 --> 00:55:51.600
that she could go and well, she would call those places.

00:55:51.600 --> 00:55:56.320
And when she would get there, they would say they have a vacancy, of course.

00:55:56.320 --> 00:56:03.320
And then when you got there and they saw who she was, we don't rent the Negroes.

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:04.320
So that was it.

00:56:04.320 --> 00:56:07.160
She had to go on to the next place.

00:56:07.160 --> 00:56:08.160
And so she went there.

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:10.200
She couldn't find a place to live.

00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:16.840
And even though she would call and say they had a place, but when she got there, they didn't

00:56:16.840 --> 00:56:17.840
have one.

00:56:17.840 --> 00:56:19.680
They had just rented it or something.

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:30.280
So she had to stay in the Y until she could find a place to live.

00:56:30.800 --> 00:56:36.160
I met her because I was planning to go into business and I was going to leave teaching

00:56:36.160 --> 00:56:46.120
and I went to sell new automobiles to kind of get into the field and business.

00:56:46.120 --> 00:56:51.800
And when I went in there, she was buying a car so she could get back and forth.

00:56:51.800 --> 00:56:58.000
The sales guy introduced us and asked if I would show her where general dynamics was.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:02.080
And she had only been in San Diego over a day or two.

00:57:02.080 --> 00:57:07.600
And so I said, yes.

00:57:07.600 --> 00:57:09.840
She complained when she went back.

00:57:09.840 --> 00:57:15.360
She complained to the cleaning lady who was black at the Y.

00:57:15.360 --> 00:57:20.320
And she said, well, she can't find a place to live.

00:57:20.320 --> 00:57:26.920
And so the sales lady said, honey, what you should do.

00:57:26.920 --> 00:57:28.960
As a man in town, you should call.

00:57:28.960 --> 00:57:33.040
You call how brown.

00:57:33.040 --> 00:57:38.640
And so she said, that sounded familiar.

00:57:38.640 --> 00:57:47.040
So anyhow, that's how I met her and I started showing her around to find a place to live.

00:57:47.040 --> 00:57:56.400
Finally, I was acquainted with an apartment where one of my fellow teachers, I was

00:57:56.400 --> 00:57:59.440
a little bit of a living place.

00:57:59.440 --> 00:58:04.480
We had had a little party or something over to her house and I remembered that and I thought

00:58:04.480 --> 00:58:06.000
that was a nice apartment.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:08.520
So I said, this would be a nice place for you to live.

00:58:08.520 --> 00:58:11.680
Showed her that and she said, oh, yeah, it's nice.

00:58:11.680 --> 00:58:15.960
It had a pool there.

00:58:15.960 --> 00:58:24.080
So she went in and talked to the manager and the manager said, well, she called first and

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:25.960
he said he had an opening.

00:58:25.960 --> 00:58:35.080
And when she went by there and he said, no, he said, well, we just can't rent to knee

00:58:35.080 --> 00:58:36.800
girls.

00:58:36.800 --> 00:58:45.040
And so she said, well, why don't you say, well, the owner who lives in Canada, I think

00:58:45.040 --> 00:58:52.320
he said, doesn't want us to rent to knee girls.

00:58:52.320 --> 00:59:00.840
So I was with her and I was sitting over there while she was talking with him and then I got

00:59:00.840 --> 00:59:03.920
up and I said, I don't believe that.

00:59:03.920 --> 00:59:07.560
And he said, well, that's what he said, no, I don't believe that.

00:59:07.560 --> 00:59:09.480
I said, here's what I'll do.

00:59:09.480 --> 00:59:15.920
I'll go around, you and I will go around to each apartment and we'll knock on the door

00:59:15.920 --> 00:59:24.500
and we'll ask that tenant whether or not they would mind or object to living next to a

00:59:24.500 --> 00:59:28.360
person who was a Negro.

00:59:28.360 --> 00:59:29.880
I had a little thing on my sleeve.

00:59:29.880 --> 00:59:36.880
I was going to go to my friends place first in her apartment.

00:59:36.880 --> 00:59:38.120
But he wouldn't do that.

00:59:38.120 --> 00:59:40.600
He said, oh, no, no, no, no.

00:59:40.600 --> 00:59:44.920
So he said, I'll see what we can do.

00:59:45.160 --> 00:59:48.160
We left.

00:59:48.160 --> 00:59:55.120
She called back, I guess, the neighbor's next day or so and he said, no, he said the owner

00:59:55.120 --> 00:59:59.640
and Canada just didn't want to rent to a Negro.

00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:06.440
And so I said, well, you know, I'll tell you what I'm going to do.

01:00:06.440 --> 01:00:17.200
I'm going to round up a hundred of my black friends and we're coming over to your apartment

01:00:17.200 --> 01:00:21.440
building and we're going to take off our clothes.

01:00:21.440 --> 01:00:25.920
We'll have our bathing suit songs and we're all going to get in that pool.

01:00:25.920 --> 01:00:33.520
He said, no, no, I'll tell you what.

01:00:33.520 --> 01:00:34.800
I think we can.

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:39.040
I think we can rent that rent rent to your apartment.

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:41.440
And that's how she got the apartment.

01:00:41.440 --> 01:00:44.240
I had to threaten them with that.

01:00:44.240 --> 01:00:49.040
And I guess that imagery was just too much to see all these black folks.

01:00:49.040 --> 01:00:59.000
And then all his, those people that he was referring to about moving out, I guess he

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:03.080
visualized everything, all be going if we did that.

01:01:03.080 --> 01:01:06.960
So anyhow, that's how she finally got to move in.

01:01:06.960 --> 01:01:11.720
So discrimination in housing was terrible.

01:01:11.720 --> 01:01:20.480
There were covenants, of course, in places in all the places in the homes and things where

01:01:20.480 --> 01:01:26.320
the people couldn't sell their home to a black person.

01:01:26.320 --> 01:01:34.960
And so we had a lot of demonstrations against the California Real Estate Association.

01:01:34.960 --> 01:01:47.480
And of course we picketed and had sit-ins at various places trying to get jobs for blacks

01:01:47.480 --> 01:01:49.960
back in those years.

01:01:49.960 --> 01:02:00.800
And our biggest project was against the Bank of America, which that's where I received

01:02:00.800 --> 01:02:06.640
my jail sentences from the Bank of America demonstrations and also from the San Diego

01:02:06.640 --> 01:02:10.520
Gas and Electric demonstrations.

01:02:10.520 --> 01:02:14.560
And what were the goals there, especially with Bank of America?

01:02:14.960 --> 01:02:25.320
We wanted them to open their employment to knee-grows back in those years and be the same

01:02:25.320 --> 01:02:28.000
thing for the San Diego Gas & Electric.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:33.800
So at that time I was chairman of the Western Region of CORE.

01:02:33.800 --> 01:02:45.480
And so we had decided that we would have a movement, a demonstration, and we would take

01:02:45.480 --> 01:02:50.600
action against Bank of America throughout the state of California.

01:02:50.600 --> 01:02:51.600
And that's what we did.

01:02:51.600 --> 01:02:54.000
What did the Western Region cover?

01:02:54.000 --> 01:03:09.600
All the states from I think we even included Colorado, but in California, in Oregon, in Washington.

01:03:09.600 --> 01:03:13.760
You had really risen up in national CORE.

01:03:13.760 --> 01:03:27.880
Yeah, I was on the advisory council, National Advisory Council.

01:03:27.880 --> 01:03:42.480
That's where James L. Farmer Jr and I became friends in Floyd, McKissick, and I became friends.

01:03:42.480 --> 01:03:53.800
We had quite a project against the Bank of America and the results were so good.

01:03:53.800 --> 01:03:58.800
Although the Bank of America would never admit it.

01:03:58.800 --> 01:04:09.040
But we forced the Bank of America and the San Diego Gas & Electric to start

01:04:09.040 --> 01:04:15.920
hiring knee-grows and they did.

01:04:15.920 --> 01:04:24.880
They would not talk to me directly, but they would talk to one of the ministers in the

01:04:24.880 --> 01:04:32.840
community about could they find some knee-grows that come down and apply for jobs and everything.

01:04:32.840 --> 01:04:36.600
So the minister and I were friends.

01:04:36.600 --> 01:04:40.400
So I don't know, I got to know that.

01:04:40.400 --> 01:04:41.400
But they did.

01:04:41.400 --> 01:04:50.920
They hired and I argued in court that my defense was that if you look at the results.

01:04:50.920 --> 01:04:55.480
But of course the prosecutor, the law is the law.

01:04:55.480 --> 01:04:56.480
You broke the law.

01:04:56.480 --> 01:04:58.480
You got it for trespassing.

01:04:58.480 --> 01:05:00.480
So you broke the law?

01:05:00.480 --> 01:05:01.480
For protest?

01:05:01.480 --> 01:05:02.480
Yeah.

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:05.800
So what were the strategies that you used?

01:05:05.800 --> 01:05:14.000
We had marches and we had sit-ins.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:17.640
We had mail-ins.

01:05:17.640 --> 01:05:26.480
We had SDG and E. We had mail-ins where we would mail-ins.

01:05:26.480 --> 01:05:34.200
Get people to mail insured of their balance due for the month.

01:05:34.200 --> 01:05:46.280
We would send either over or under and just kind of a nuisance factor.

01:05:46.280 --> 01:05:52.360
But it was effective.

01:05:52.360 --> 01:06:01.320
The coin in was we would stand in line at the Tellers window.

01:06:01.320 --> 01:06:12.200
We would have a lot of pennies with us and we would either ask for pennies.

01:06:12.200 --> 01:06:16.720
We would give them $10 and we would ask for some change.

01:06:16.720 --> 01:06:19.680
We would stand there and count all the pennies.

01:06:19.680 --> 01:06:23.560
We would bring pennies with us.

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:26.160
We got to the front of the window.

01:06:26.160 --> 01:06:34.640
We would make our deposit or whatever we would do and we count out pennies one at a time

01:06:34.640 --> 01:06:46.280
one at a time while the others were sitting on the floor singing our songs and things.

01:06:46.280 --> 01:06:53.240
That was very effective.

01:06:53.240 --> 01:06:57.480
It created some real results.

01:06:57.480 --> 01:07:01.360
You look at those banks and things now.

01:07:01.360 --> 01:07:11.360
Of course I always point out, I'm not saying that San Diego Corps take full credit for that.

01:07:11.360 --> 01:07:16.320
There was a national movement going on.

01:07:16.320 --> 01:07:27.880
In that context, we were able to be very effective and we laid it on the line.

01:07:27.880 --> 01:07:34.480
We laid our jobs on the line.

01:07:34.480 --> 01:07:52.600
I was called to appear in Sacramento at the board of trustees who were over the education

01:07:52.600 --> 01:07:53.960
state superintendent and so forth.

01:07:53.960 --> 01:08:06.000
I was called to come there to explain why I should not have my teaching credential removed

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:11.280
because of my leadership in Corps.

01:08:11.280 --> 01:08:23.480
I had a lawyer who was in Corps as well and he went with me up to go to defend myself.

01:08:23.480 --> 01:08:30.480
I don't know if it was just a scare tactic or they couldn't didn't want to pursue it

01:08:30.480 --> 01:08:35.560
but they didn't take my credential.

01:08:35.560 --> 01:08:40.560
That was a scary time.

01:08:40.560 --> 01:08:42.560
Still it's intimidation.

01:08:42.560 --> 01:08:46.800
That's a really intimidation.

01:08:46.800 --> 01:08:51.320
That was, we did well.

01:08:51.320 --> 01:08:54.280
We served our jail times.

01:08:54.280 --> 01:09:01.640
We were able to serve our jail times on weekends.

01:09:01.640 --> 01:09:06.280
I was still teaching school.

01:09:06.280 --> 01:09:09.280
That's my wife.

01:09:09.280 --> 01:09:18.400
I was teaching school and they said, well, you can serve as time on weekends, which I did.

01:09:18.400 --> 01:09:23.200
There was only really effective times back then.

01:09:23.200 --> 01:09:26.880
That was the core effort in this area, largely African-American.

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:28.080
Was it an interracial form of a question?

01:09:28.080 --> 01:09:29.080
That's a good question.

01:09:29.080 --> 01:09:39.160
I always point out to people that during those years there were more white members than

01:09:39.160 --> 01:09:42.240
there were black members.

01:09:42.240 --> 01:09:53.640
There were blacks and whites and the whites were probably two-thirds of the chapter.

01:09:53.640 --> 01:10:04.240
I can remember going out strongly trying to recruit blacks to become members of Corps

01:10:04.240 --> 01:10:09.360
or just to participate in some way with Corps.

01:10:09.360 --> 01:10:15.000
Membership dues was $25.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:22.520
Everyone could afford it but there were the times where blacks did.

01:10:22.520 --> 01:10:31.160
In my opinion, we're very much afraid to be involved in the civil rights movement.

01:10:31.160 --> 01:10:32.160
We didn't have any.

01:10:32.160 --> 01:10:37.960
It took a lot of work to try to get them involved.

01:10:37.960 --> 01:10:45.840
Even at our national meetings, we would discuss that a lot and at our national convention.

01:10:45.840 --> 01:10:51.160
We had a big thing about trying to get more blacks involved.

01:10:51.160 --> 01:10:57.560
I spent a lot of time on trying to do that.

01:10:57.560 --> 01:10:59.040
That was tough.

01:10:59.040 --> 01:11:04.480
The civil rights movement did not participate in the civil rights movement here in San

01:11:04.480 --> 01:11:07.000
Diego to any degree.

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:09.280
What do you think that was?

01:11:09.280 --> 01:11:17.600
I think it's because they were fearful of reprisals.

01:11:17.600 --> 01:11:22.360
They did not want to risk whatever they had.

01:11:22.360 --> 01:11:29.000
Of course, our comeback was, you don't have very much to begin with.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:35.640
But whatever they had, they just did not want to risk that.

01:11:35.640 --> 01:11:37.840
There were comments that would come back to me.

01:11:37.840 --> 01:11:50.000
I would never be able to keep my job because they would find a way to fire me.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:53.160
There was some attempt, I guess.

01:11:53.160 --> 01:12:04.160
They just did not want to risk that even to the point where they would even admit to

01:12:04.160 --> 01:12:12.000
their white friends that they even knew me, friends of mine.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:15.320
It was pretty bad back in those days.

01:12:15.320 --> 01:12:19.800
Whatever they had, they didn't want to risk losing it.

01:12:19.800 --> 01:12:25.160
What were the historic origins of the Black community here?

01:12:25.160 --> 01:12:26.160
Where did people come from?

01:12:26.160 --> 01:12:30.800
Were they mostly the port or a war industry?

01:12:30.800 --> 01:12:32.040
What brought people?

01:12:32.040 --> 01:12:41.120
I understand that number came through the Navy.

01:12:41.120 --> 01:12:52.120
A lot had no surveys or any research on it.

01:12:52.120 --> 01:13:00.720
It seemed from talking with people that a number of people came from Texas area.

01:13:00.720 --> 01:13:05.920
My understanding is they were introduced to San Diego through the Navy.

01:13:05.920 --> 01:13:11.600
Some people got here, I don't know how, out there in a place called Ramona up there

01:13:11.600 --> 01:13:18.000
that there were Negroes that settled there.

01:13:18.000 --> 01:13:27.960
Back I don't know when that was, it was probably either the very early 1900s or late 1800s.

01:13:27.960 --> 01:13:32.560
Another thing that's going to ask you back is asking about the interracial organization.

01:13:32.560 --> 01:13:36.960
Is it already a large Latino population in San Diego at that time?

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:37.960
No.

01:13:37.960 --> 01:13:40.960
There was not a large Latino population.

01:13:40.960 --> 01:13:53.440
In fact, I don't know the stats on it.

01:13:53.440 --> 01:14:00.680
Over in Logan Heights, that was known as a Black community.

01:14:00.680 --> 01:14:05.080
There were very few Latinos living there.

01:14:05.080 --> 01:14:12.080
Now, I think it's two thirds of Latino.

01:14:12.080 --> 01:14:16.320
No, there just weren't very many.

01:14:16.320 --> 01:14:28.360
The Mexican population was evidently very small back then because they certainly weren't visible.

01:14:28.360 --> 01:14:32.680
That came later.

01:14:32.680 --> 01:14:36.960
Another thing I wanted to ask about was other civil rights organizations.

01:14:36.960 --> 01:14:45.160
You're here with COAR, but we're talking about early 60s when you have the student's

01:14:45.160 --> 01:14:51.920
sit-in movement happening in other places, freedom rides, etc.

01:14:51.920 --> 01:14:55.880
Were there other organizations that came into this area or that you were in contact with

01:14:55.880 --> 01:14:59.040
and worked with or that you were paying attention to from afar?

01:14:59.040 --> 01:15:09.520
The only organizations were the end of WACP, the Urban League.

01:15:09.520 --> 01:15:15.680
Those were the only other organizations.

01:15:15.680 --> 01:15:22.080
The end of WACP at that time was practically invisible.

01:15:22.080 --> 01:15:30.640
They had no participation with us in the civil rights movement in San Diego.

01:15:30.640 --> 01:15:39.840
The Urban League had no participation with us in the civil rights movement, but they

01:15:39.840 --> 01:15:40.840
were here.

01:15:40.840 --> 01:15:41.840
They were present.

01:15:41.840 --> 01:15:42.840
You could contact them.

01:15:42.840 --> 01:15:43.840
They end up WACP.

01:15:43.840 --> 01:15:47.120
I say, not exaggerating.

01:15:47.120 --> 01:15:51.600
I tried to find them and join them.

01:15:51.600 --> 01:15:54.680
I understand I did.

01:15:54.680 --> 01:15:55.680
I couldn't.

01:15:55.680 --> 01:16:03.160
Wherever they were supposed to have an office, it wasn't open and the call couldn't contact

01:16:03.160 --> 01:16:04.560
them.

01:16:04.560 --> 01:16:08.760
I tried and tried.

01:16:08.760 --> 01:16:20.080
The only organization other than CORE was, as I mentioned earlier, the Afro-American Association.

01:16:20.080 --> 01:16:23.600
Did that continue or did that also fade out?

01:16:23.600 --> 01:16:26.680
That faded out.

01:16:26.680 --> 01:16:35.280
I became so involved in CORE and I don't know really what happened to it, but it kind

01:16:35.280 --> 01:16:38.320
of just faded.

01:16:38.320 --> 01:16:46.120
If you can keep us going with your involvement with CORE, so we're in the early 60s now,

01:16:46.120 --> 01:16:51.280
they just take us forward.

01:16:51.280 --> 01:17:01.040
One of the things that I did not mention, which I'm going to try to write about include

01:17:01.040 --> 01:17:08.240
this part of it, is what people didn't actually realize about.

01:17:08.240 --> 01:17:17.360
CORE was an organization that had internal problems too.

01:17:17.360 --> 01:17:29.640
I was in a position where I was not only fighting white racism on the outside, but I was fighting

01:17:29.640 --> 01:17:34.680
from the inside.

01:17:34.680 --> 01:17:43.840
That opposition was in the form of, and I really don't know.

01:17:43.840 --> 01:17:55.720
People, it was rumored by private citizens as well as the FBI.

01:17:55.720 --> 01:18:03.320
We had the same problem as other chapters throughout the country had with infiltration

01:18:03.320 --> 01:18:05.320
of other groups.

01:18:05.320 --> 01:18:16.960
I only know that the peace movement was the only group that I knew was wanted to become

01:18:16.960 --> 01:18:24.920
active in our organization and to exert some influence on what we did.

01:18:24.920 --> 01:18:39.840
I refused that because I was very myopic in my view that we had enough on our plate

01:18:39.840 --> 01:18:48.760
in our minds to try to conquer this racial problem against Negroes and America.

01:18:48.760 --> 01:18:51.960
We had enough to do with that.

01:18:51.960 --> 01:19:03.120
I was not interested in trying to use my personal resources and energy to take on some other

01:19:03.120 --> 01:19:05.800
battles like the peace movement and so on.

01:19:05.800 --> 01:19:11.000
The other issue was communism and Trotskyites.

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:17.040
I didn't know what the Trotskyites was.

01:19:18.040 --> 01:19:26.000
The first thing I heard about communism was in high school and in history books, but

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:29.000
I didn't know anything about it.

01:19:29.000 --> 01:19:33.440
They tried to accuse us of being communist.

01:19:33.440 --> 01:19:35.440
I didn't know what they were talking about.

01:19:35.440 --> 01:19:45.760
Anyhow, that was a way of labeling us the core and other organizations that you've been

01:19:45.760 --> 01:19:50.160
infiltrated, communism and so on.

01:19:50.160 --> 01:19:52.560
There was a battle.

01:19:52.560 --> 01:19:54.880
I couldn't identify it.

01:19:54.880 --> 01:20:01.000
I couldn't label it with any particular name, but there was a tremendous battle inside

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:14.320
our organization to oust me and take over the leadership with another person and another

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:17.880
group.

01:20:17.880 --> 01:20:28.120
Those were some really, really, really tumultuous times and quite painful.

01:20:28.120 --> 01:20:38.240
More painful, I would say, than the fight against the companies that were segregating,

01:20:38.240 --> 01:20:44.520
were discriminating and employment and the housing and all that stuff.

01:20:44.520 --> 01:20:53.240
It was more painful because it came from the people inside the organization, both blacks

01:20:53.240 --> 01:20:55.200
and whites.

01:20:55.200 --> 01:20:58.920
What was the result of those struggles?

01:20:58.920 --> 01:21:10.040
Well, I've never been asked that question because the truth would be that the results of that

01:21:10.040 --> 01:21:23.360
constant fighting, I can't think of a better way of fighting, was that I finally left.

01:21:23.360 --> 01:21:35.120
And it was at the end of my jail sentences where I was doing them and all that.

01:21:35.120 --> 01:21:43.040
And after that, I resigned and left and core just kind of.

01:21:43.040 --> 01:21:46.240
So after you left, you really just have offered it?

01:21:46.240 --> 01:21:49.600
When was that approximately?

01:21:49.600 --> 01:21:53.800
I think it was 67.

01:21:53.800 --> 01:22:04.400
I think there was an attempt by a friend of mine to take over the leadership.

01:22:04.400 --> 01:22:21.040
But then when we left and went to DC for preparing to go over into Africa, Peace Corps,

01:22:21.040 --> 01:22:43.880
my understanding was that the black power movement, the black panther movement and the

01:22:43.880 --> 01:22:45.600
US Organization.

01:22:45.600 --> 01:22:49.760
You remember the US Organization, there was a problem in San Diego.

01:22:49.760 --> 01:22:57.600
And I was gone, so all of this is hearsay, but there was a lot of fighting between those

01:22:57.600 --> 01:23:01.840
two organizations and so on.

01:23:01.840 --> 01:23:03.360
And that really came in after you left.

01:23:03.360 --> 01:23:05.080
Yeah, I wasn't here to see it.

01:23:05.080 --> 01:23:06.080
You didn't even arrive.

01:23:06.080 --> 01:23:12.440
I wasn't here and so core just kind of, I guess, faded away.

01:23:12.440 --> 01:23:16.440
And then the sort of another way of came in behind it.

01:23:16.440 --> 01:23:19.360
And that was pretty temporary.

01:23:19.360 --> 01:23:23.760
I mean, there was a lot of fighting and stuff that went on.

01:23:23.760 --> 01:23:32.040
But I don't think there was anyone that really grabbed onto the issues and pursued those

01:23:32.040 --> 01:23:36.640
issues or tried to replace core or anything.

01:23:36.640 --> 01:23:39.840
They just, I don't really understand it now.

01:23:39.840 --> 01:23:57.640
It's what happened, but it just seemed to fade away us and black panthers, at least

01:23:57.640 --> 01:23:58.640
in San Diego.

01:23:58.640 --> 01:24:00.440
At least in San Diego, right?

01:24:00.440 --> 01:24:01.440
Right.

01:24:01.440 --> 01:24:04.960
So then you were in Lesotho for a couple of years?

01:24:04.960 --> 01:24:09.640
No, I was there for one year, just a little under a year.

01:24:09.640 --> 01:24:10.640
Okay.

01:24:10.640 --> 01:24:21.000
That's another story in itself in that I always find, because of the way I grew up and the

01:24:21.000 --> 01:24:25.360
family I grew up, I always find humor in a lot of these tragedies.

01:24:25.360 --> 01:24:34.560
But when we went there, Lesotho is a country that's completely surrounded by South Africa.

01:24:34.560 --> 01:24:40.320
And so getting in and out, you had to go through South Africa.

01:24:40.320 --> 01:24:49.240
So when my wife and I went over to Lesotho, we had to stop in Johannesburg.

01:24:49.240 --> 01:24:57.440
And so we were waiting for the flight to take us to Lesotho the next morning.

01:24:57.440 --> 01:25:06.680
And so of course, apartheid was very strong.

01:25:06.680 --> 01:25:17.160
So what they did was they had some room that was above the airport somewhere.

01:25:17.160 --> 01:25:21.520
And that was for blacks.

01:25:21.520 --> 01:25:24.400
That put you had to stay in that room.

01:25:24.400 --> 01:25:26.320
You couldn't be in the airport anywhere.

01:25:26.320 --> 01:25:30.160
You had to stay in that room until you're flight left.

01:25:30.160 --> 01:25:33.000
Now these were for Africans.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:35.320
And I was African then.

01:25:35.320 --> 01:25:38.520
You know, I mean, it was the first time I was considered African.

01:25:38.520 --> 01:25:41.800
Well, they put us up there in that room.

01:25:41.800 --> 01:25:43.040
And we stayed there.

01:25:43.040 --> 01:25:50.120
So I decided next morning that I was going to test it and just get out and walk around

01:25:50.120 --> 01:25:52.840
the airport to see you.

01:25:52.840 --> 01:25:55.600
And I did that.

01:25:55.600 --> 01:26:05.520
And the next day I heard it was over the PA system that you know, the Harold Brown report

01:26:05.520 --> 01:26:07.560
to such and such and such.

01:26:07.560 --> 01:26:18.240
And my wife saw the some guys coming and chatting, standing around, chatting, chatting.

01:26:18.240 --> 01:26:24.280
And she was getting worried because her full husband was out there going, you know,

01:26:24.280 --> 01:26:26.800
probably get jailed and so forth.

01:26:26.800 --> 01:26:27.800
It's out there.

01:26:27.800 --> 01:26:39.520
But anyhow, one guy came up to me and I suspect that he was from the United States Embassy.

01:26:39.520 --> 01:26:44.280
He came up to me and it kind of stood and looked the other way.

01:26:44.280 --> 01:26:47.240
And Wispens had, is everything all right?

01:26:47.240 --> 01:26:58.280
And I looked and said, yeah, as far as I'm concerned, you know, it's okay.

01:26:58.280 --> 01:27:05.200
So we finally got, they got me back and the plane came and we're off to Lesotho.

01:27:05.200 --> 01:27:09.040
And so now we are landing Lesotho.

01:27:09.040 --> 01:27:14.920
There's a black Prime Minister Chief Leabua Jonathan and so on.

01:27:14.920 --> 01:27:22.200
And we landed and the people seemed to be pretty joyous, you know.

01:27:22.200 --> 01:27:26.240
My wife and I, two African Americans, two blacks.

01:27:26.240 --> 01:27:33.720
I mean, blacks, we were African.

01:27:33.720 --> 01:27:37.800
You know, and that's a term we use in America, blacks.

01:27:37.800 --> 01:27:40.880
We were Africans.

01:27:40.880 --> 01:27:44.280
So we turned in and they seemed to be, you know, greeted us well.

01:27:44.280 --> 01:27:46.400
And so everything was really nice.

01:27:46.400 --> 01:27:55.600
And then sometime later, maybe a month or so later, the Peace Corps volunteers came.

01:27:55.600 --> 01:28:04.240
And so they'd land in the airport and coming out of those planes or all these white students,

01:28:04.240 --> 01:28:05.240
you know.

01:28:05.480 --> 01:28:13.520
It was really funny because I can imagine how Lesotho, the Fed, they were in shop

01:28:13.520 --> 01:28:16.800
because they saw us and they knew anything about the Peace Corps.

01:28:16.800 --> 01:28:19.560
They thought, oh, it's Peace Corps.

01:28:19.560 --> 01:28:23.000
You know, Peace Corps, their mind was black.

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:25.520
And they saw all those whites.

01:28:25.520 --> 01:28:31.920
And we had about, I think, three blacks Peace Corps workers.

01:28:31.920 --> 01:28:38.440
So they came off and then, of course, the war was on.

01:28:38.440 --> 01:28:50.320
We were, the Peace Corps was accused of all kinds of things, you know, and spying on the

01:28:50.320 --> 01:28:55.440
Soutu and we just went on and on for that time.

01:28:55.440 --> 01:28:58.000
And then while we were there.

01:28:58.000 --> 01:29:01.680
And you were one of the directors of the program in New York.

01:29:01.680 --> 01:29:03.600
Yeah, I was a deputy, deputy director.

01:29:03.600 --> 01:29:04.600
Deputy director.

01:29:04.600 --> 01:29:07.440
So were you being called in to answer to these things?

01:29:07.440 --> 01:29:08.440
Or, no.

01:29:08.440 --> 01:29:11.360
I mean, amble PR or no.

01:29:11.360 --> 01:29:18.920
We had a Chargé d'Affaires and not an ambassador, a Chargé d'Affaires, but no, he never consulted

01:29:18.920 --> 01:29:19.920
me.

01:29:20.920 --> 01:29:28.160
I was invited to speak to, by different people in Maseru.

01:29:28.160 --> 01:29:32.400
It's a capital to speak to their schools and so forth.

01:29:32.400 --> 01:29:39.840
And there's this Negro Americans here, you know, which they've never seen before.

01:29:39.840 --> 01:29:49.840
And I did and never asked me about, about what they called us about.

01:29:49.840 --> 01:29:55.160
I guess, Africans in America, blacks in America.

01:29:55.160 --> 01:30:01.200
And I would tell them, you know, they were, they were pretty sophisticated to many of them.

01:30:01.200 --> 01:30:05.600
They knew what was going on around the country and they would ask all these questions about

01:30:05.600 --> 01:30:08.080
how we were treated in America.

01:30:08.080 --> 01:30:14.680
And I'd tell, you know, the truth, just like I'm answering questions here, I would tell.

01:30:14.680 --> 01:30:20.120
Well, evidently, you know, we got back to the Chargé d'Affaires and his people and they

01:30:20.120 --> 01:30:27.960
didn't like that because I was exposing America, I guess.

01:30:27.960 --> 01:30:29.640
That's still the problem we have today.

01:30:29.640 --> 01:30:33.000
I mean, that's why we're doing history right now.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:42.400
They try to get America to know and understand what happened and what's happening now.

01:30:42.400 --> 01:30:47.600
And I go to the third step, remember, my range, what should happen in the future.

01:30:47.600 --> 01:30:51.240
But that was the situation in Lesotho.

01:30:51.240 --> 01:30:57.160
And finally, Martin Luther King was assassinated.

01:30:57.160 --> 01:30:59.920
And that was just too much for me to bear.

01:30:59.920 --> 01:31:09.440
I could remain there out of the country and while all this was going on back home.

01:31:09.440 --> 01:31:14.960
And so I told my wife to get packed because I've got to go back.

01:31:14.960 --> 01:31:15.960
And so I did.

01:31:15.960 --> 01:31:23.640
And we left and I guess the Chargé d'Affaires and we're very happy about that.

01:31:23.640 --> 01:31:24.640
So we came back and.

01:31:24.640 --> 01:31:29.240
So you had news reached you of what the response was in various cities.

01:31:29.240 --> 01:31:30.240
Yeah.

01:31:30.240 --> 01:31:31.240
Yeah.

01:31:31.240 --> 01:31:32.240
Yes.

01:31:32.240 --> 01:31:33.240
Oh, yeah.

01:31:33.240 --> 01:31:35.240
What was going on?

01:31:35.240 --> 01:31:53.720
And when Martin Luther King was killed, I went to the church to the AME church, African

01:31:53.720 --> 01:31:58.240
Methodist Episcopal Church there in Lesotho.

01:31:58.240 --> 01:32:06.240
And I asked we could have a memorial service there for Martin.

01:32:06.240 --> 01:32:08.800
And he said, oh, yeah, of course.

01:32:08.800 --> 01:32:18.240
And so we put together a really nice memorial service in honor of Martin.

01:32:18.240 --> 01:32:26.800
And at the whole time we were there and before we got there, King Moshoeshoe II of Lesotho was

01:32:26.800 --> 01:32:37.320
under house arrest because he opposed apartheid.

01:32:37.320 --> 01:32:47.200
And the people were able to put in a Prime Minister Chief Leabua Jonathan who, whether he agreed with the partied

01:32:47.200 --> 01:32:50.360
and not he went along with the partied.

01:32:50.360 --> 01:32:54.040
But the king was sort of imprisoned.

01:32:54.040 --> 01:33:06.040
So when we had this church memorial service who walks in the king almost brings tears

01:33:06.040 --> 01:33:08.240
to my eyes now.

01:33:08.240 --> 01:33:16.600
He walked in and set in through the whole service.

01:33:16.600 --> 01:33:27.200
And I gave the remarks and so forth with an interpreter.

01:33:27.200 --> 01:33:32.280
And my wife sang for him.

01:33:32.280 --> 01:33:39.480
And then we had some talks by some of the Basotho leaders.

01:33:39.480 --> 01:33:43.440
And it was just a beautiful, beautiful ceremony.

01:33:43.440 --> 01:33:53.440
But when the king came in, you know, there's in South Africa, you probably have heard

01:33:53.440 --> 01:33:55.440
this.

01:33:55.440 --> 01:34:07.120
The ladies give a kind of a thrilling, a good, ululation.

01:34:07.120 --> 01:34:12.840
It's just a sound that is, but it's high.

01:34:12.840 --> 01:34:17.840
And so, you know, when he came in, it was just that.

01:34:17.840 --> 01:34:27.640
You know, that we had been invited to his palace a couple times for a wife and a half.

01:34:27.640 --> 01:34:31.800
But when he walked in there, boy, it was really something.

01:34:31.800 --> 01:34:36.840
So after that, and you know, we were packed and everything.

01:34:36.840 --> 01:34:44.920
And it came back to the States and went through the out processing of the Peace Corps and

01:34:44.920 --> 01:34:49.960
did up trying to get back to San Diego.

01:34:49.960 --> 01:34:52.640
And I couldn't find a position.

01:34:52.640 --> 01:35:02.040
So that's where in the Florida, McKissick, and I started this company in Harlem, Florida

01:35:02.040 --> 01:35:04.640
McKissick Enterprises.

01:35:04.640 --> 01:35:09.240
And so I worked there for, I don't know, last lesson of year.

01:35:09.240 --> 01:35:13.440
And then I moved to the, to the bank.

01:35:13.440 --> 01:35:16.240
And I worked for Marine Midland Bank.

01:35:16.240 --> 01:35:17.240
For which bank?

01:35:17.240 --> 01:35:22.680
Marine Midland, and my DLA, and the home wall street.

01:35:22.680 --> 01:35:26.200
And I did that.

01:35:26.200 --> 01:35:34.600
And then from there, I was asked to come back by an old friend of mine who had been exposed

01:35:34.880 --> 01:35:37.840
to corps when I was leading corps.

01:35:37.840 --> 01:35:42.680
He wasn't a member, but he was around and knew.

01:35:42.680 --> 01:35:48.400
And then he kind of became a little involved, not really.

01:35:48.400 --> 01:35:51.000
But he and I got to know each other.

01:35:51.000 --> 01:35:58.960
And so he had become a student, along with some others at San Diego State.

01:35:58.960 --> 01:36:06.560
And they started, we're trying to start a black studies program.

01:36:06.560 --> 01:36:10.600
And again, more in fighting and so forth.

01:36:10.600 --> 01:36:13.520
And so they couldn't really get it going and everything.

01:36:13.520 --> 01:36:17.000
So he called me in New York.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:20.880
And I was a, you know, loan officer there at the bank.

01:36:20.880 --> 01:36:28.920
And he said, asked me what I could, but I'd be interested in come back to San Diego.

01:36:28.920 --> 01:36:33.760
Well, you know, I've been trying to get back to San Diego all this time.

01:36:33.760 --> 01:36:41.880
So I said, well, it was a position where I would be assistant to the president.

01:36:41.880 --> 01:36:51.920
And I thought about it because Wells Fargo had been holding the position for me also,

01:36:51.920 --> 01:36:55.520
but they could meet my salary requirement.

01:36:55.520 --> 01:36:59.760
And so I was just kind of waiting that out.

01:36:59.760 --> 01:37:07.360
But my wife was, she was just happy she could be to get back to San Diego.

01:37:07.360 --> 01:37:11.000
So I said, yes, so we came back to San Diego.

01:37:11.000 --> 01:37:17.840
And then that's when I started working in September of 1971 at San Diego State.

01:37:17.840 --> 01:37:26.920
And I was, you know, my plan was to organize that program,

01:37:26.920 --> 01:37:31.480
plus some other responsibilities that I had on the campus.

01:37:31.480 --> 01:37:38.680
But my plan was to get into the business area.

01:37:38.680 --> 01:37:41.800
And I understand you're hiring some grounds.

01:37:41.800 --> 01:37:42.760
Yeah.

01:37:42.760 --> 01:37:49.440
Yeah, I was the first black administrator that the university had ever had.

01:37:49.440 --> 01:38:00.920
And also, I, during my first year there, I hired some faculty members.

01:38:00.920 --> 01:38:08.520
I hired from other who had just finished their PhDs.

01:38:08.520 --> 01:38:16.640
And we're working at other universities and I hired them and brought them to San Diego State.

01:38:16.640 --> 01:38:23.760
And then we've established a curriculum.

01:38:23.760 --> 01:38:29.880
We established a major and a minor in back in that.

01:38:29.880 --> 01:38:34.920
Those were very early years in black studies.

01:38:34.920 --> 01:38:44.480
And I was able to get the university to accept our courses to fulfill the general education

01:38:44.480 --> 01:38:46.520
requirements just like all the others.

01:38:46.520 --> 01:38:49.480
I mean, that was a major coup.

01:38:49.480 --> 01:38:56.800
And so that's one of the things I'm most proud of really.

01:38:56.800 --> 01:39:04.040
So we got that major and got a minor and had our general education required courses.

01:39:04.040 --> 01:39:15.680
And we went on and my plan was to do that for a year and then pursue my administrative career,

01:39:15.680 --> 01:39:23.640
which my goal was to become a president of a college or university eventually.

01:39:23.640 --> 01:39:34.920
And I had to stay there to finish what I wanted to finish in the Afro American Studies program

01:39:34.920 --> 01:39:36.000
for two years.

01:39:36.000 --> 01:39:41.320
And then I left and went over and

01:39:41.320 --> 01:39:50.080
to the became the director of the computer services for the university.

01:39:50.080 --> 01:39:58.320
I did the other administrative things on campus and I left the program and it was, you know,

01:39:58.320 --> 01:40:03.240
it's now a full fledged department.

01:40:03.240 --> 01:40:08.760
They changed the name to Africana Studies, rather than African American Studies.

01:40:08.760 --> 01:40:16.400
But it's a full fledged department in San Diego State.

01:40:16.400 --> 01:40:19.800
And you still retain ties, at least emotional ties, too?

01:40:19.800 --> 01:40:29.360
Yeah, emotional, but I've been away since, but that was 73.

01:40:29.360 --> 01:40:31.800
And that was your baby?

01:40:31.800 --> 01:40:33.800
Yeah, that's right.

01:40:33.800 --> 01:40:37.040
Baby is grown.

01:40:37.040 --> 01:40:42.400
So that was a good experience.

01:40:42.400 --> 01:40:46.320
And then you saw you went on to do other things at San Diego State.

01:40:46.320 --> 01:41:02.480
And it became the associate dean of the within the administrative, I forget the title of

01:41:02.480 --> 01:41:03.480
forget.

01:41:03.480 --> 01:41:11.840
It was an associate dean of an administration, I forget what that was.

01:41:11.840 --> 01:41:18.240
But then I went on to take the president asked me to head up the computer services for the

01:41:18.240 --> 01:41:20.480
university.

01:41:20.480 --> 01:41:23.760
And I did that.

01:41:23.760 --> 01:41:32.440
And then in 1980, I went to become the associate dean in the College of Business Administration

01:41:32.440 --> 01:41:44.760
and that's where I retired from there after, I guess, 26 years as the associate dean there.

01:41:44.760 --> 01:41:49.280
And then I went into real estate development.

01:41:49.280 --> 01:41:52.080
And that's what I'm still involved with.

01:41:52.080 --> 01:41:53.080
Yeah.

01:41:53.080 --> 01:42:02.000
And I retired from San Diego State in 2004, but I had dangled in real estate.

01:42:02.000 --> 01:42:07.040
During my later years.

01:42:07.040 --> 01:42:22.280
But I'm just reminding myself before that, what I did was, in 1987, I spearheaded the formation

01:42:22.280 --> 01:42:31.280
of an organization called the Black Economic Development.

01:42:31.280 --> 01:42:39.080
And it was called the Black Economic Development Task Force.

01:42:39.080 --> 01:42:41.520
And I did that for 10 years.

01:42:41.520 --> 01:42:43.720
Was I just in San Diego?

01:42:43.720 --> 01:42:44.720
In San Diego.

01:42:44.720 --> 01:42:46.880
Did that for 10 years?

01:42:46.880 --> 01:43:04.840
And then I, as the associate dean, I founded a program, a certificate program in community

01:43:04.840 --> 01:43:12.600
economic development and developed a curriculum there.

01:43:12.600 --> 01:43:21.480
And use the faculty there in our college, in our business college, and a couple people

01:43:21.480 --> 01:43:24.520
outside the university.

01:43:24.520 --> 01:43:27.080
And that was a very successful program.

01:43:27.080 --> 01:43:31.080
I did that until I retired in 2004.

01:43:31.080 --> 01:43:33.520
And community members can participate?

01:43:33.520 --> 01:43:34.520
Yes.

01:43:34.520 --> 01:43:35.520
Yeah.

01:43:35.520 --> 01:43:42.520
Community members, we had a full, it was about an eight month program.

01:43:42.520 --> 01:43:54.880
And it turned out, but when I retired again, which I knew it would, they kept it there

01:43:54.880 --> 01:44:01.000
because that program because of me, which is crazy.

01:44:01.000 --> 01:44:04.000
But that's really a fact.

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:10.240
I knew, and so I knew, after I believe, they would let it go because they couldn't fund

01:44:10.240 --> 01:44:11.240
it.

01:44:11.240 --> 01:44:19.760
And then I raised funds to supplement what the university put into it in terms of offices

01:44:19.760 --> 01:44:24.360
and a couple of people who worked for me.

01:44:24.360 --> 01:44:31.360
But to run the program, I raised funds outside the program.

01:44:31.360 --> 01:44:36.160
Plus, it got tremendous publicity.

01:44:36.160 --> 01:44:41.360
The PR was very good, so the university liked that.

01:44:41.360 --> 01:44:46.160
But they weren't going to put in a lot of money into the program.

01:44:46.160 --> 01:45:00.960
And the program could not pay for itself because you just couldn't charge enough to make

01:45:00.960 --> 01:45:03.320
it pay for itself.

01:45:03.320 --> 01:45:10.920
You could do it in New York, charge that much at Columbia or NYU and places like that.

01:45:10.920 --> 01:45:13.160
I'm familiar with them.

01:45:13.160 --> 01:45:18.500
Their programs, they could charge a lot of money from people who would come and pay that

01:45:18.500 --> 01:45:21.320
money, but we couldn't charge that much for it.

01:45:21.320 --> 01:45:22.960
So it just couldn't pay for itself.

01:45:22.960 --> 01:45:25.880
So I knew it wasn't bringing money.

01:45:25.880 --> 01:45:29.640
And David was going to, which they did.

01:45:29.640 --> 01:45:34.400
And at this point, to you to see how these things work so hard on.

01:45:34.400 --> 01:45:42.320
But I was kind of used to it because the core disappeared.

01:45:42.320 --> 01:45:52.120
I guess I failed to mention that I founded a program called Leadership Training.

01:45:52.120 --> 01:45:58.560
As I finished core, I did that for a year.

01:45:58.560 --> 01:46:00.600
Then I went into the Peace Corps.

01:46:00.600 --> 01:46:03.520
But that was a good program.

01:46:03.520 --> 01:46:06.800
The Leadership Training Program was really great.

01:46:06.800 --> 01:46:17.120
And they got a lot of applause even from the labor department.

01:46:17.120 --> 01:46:21.800
But then that went, I went, I went into the Peace Corps.

01:46:21.800 --> 01:46:27.000
They tried to keep it going for a year, but that went poof.

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:36.440
So then I, but another thing I left out was, well, the Black Economic Development Task Force.

01:46:36.440 --> 01:46:38.680
But you did that for 10 years.

01:46:38.680 --> 01:46:46.360
And then when you're doing this, as you probably are aware of, when you're in these,

01:46:46.360 --> 01:46:48.560
not for profit organizations.

01:46:48.560 --> 01:46:54.640
I mean, you know, and you found them and you're instrumental in really getting things organized.

01:46:54.640 --> 01:46:58.960
But 90% of the work ends up with you.

01:46:58.960 --> 01:47:06.800
And so, from the Black Economic Development Task Force, that 10 after 10 years.

01:47:06.800 --> 01:47:09.880
And I said, I couldn't do it any longer.

01:47:09.880 --> 01:47:12.400
It went by the wayside.

01:47:12.400 --> 01:47:21.800
Then I formed an organization while I was at the business school called,

01:47:21.800 --> 01:47:29.560
it was an organization to bring together business, the business community,

01:47:29.560 --> 01:47:33.480
to discuss racial matters.

01:47:33.480 --> 01:47:41.560
And so I had a couple of friends who were very prominent in San Diego, multi-millionaires.

01:47:41.560 --> 01:47:46.040
And so I got the two of them to join with me.

01:47:46.040 --> 01:47:51.560
And we had that program where we met once a month at the hotel down there.

01:47:51.560 --> 01:47:59.160
We had a mission value for lunch and had these discussions about race matters.

01:47:59.160 --> 01:48:05.920
And we finally, after 10 years, I got tired and nobody took my place.

01:48:05.920 --> 01:48:11.560
And so that went by the wayside.

01:48:11.560 --> 01:48:14.120
So, have a name?

01:48:14.120 --> 01:48:28.680
Yeah, it was called, it was called, Club was the acronym Community Leaders Undoing Biasis.

01:48:28.680 --> 01:48:32.880
And that was a good group.

01:48:32.880 --> 01:48:35.680
People said they really enjoyed that.

01:48:35.680 --> 01:48:41.960
But the two guys that I brought, I mean, they have their own stuff going on and everything.

01:48:42.960 --> 01:48:46.120
I convinced them that they needed to do something in this area.

01:48:46.120 --> 01:48:49.480
And they said, okay, how?

01:48:49.480 --> 01:48:50.480
Let's go.

01:48:50.480 --> 01:48:51.480
You do it.

01:48:51.480 --> 01:48:52.480
We're with you.

01:48:52.480 --> 01:48:57.720
But they weren't going to get me and make this thing go and keep it going.

01:48:57.720 --> 01:48:59.440
So that went by the wayside.

01:48:59.440 --> 01:49:11.920
So everything that I, unfortunately, I guess some academicians would accuse me of not falling

01:49:11.920 --> 01:49:15.920
the rules of delegation.

01:49:15.920 --> 01:49:20.160
I'm not saying they were to delegate, you know.

01:49:20.160 --> 01:49:25.920
But the reply to that, I heard someone say, well, delegate to whom.

01:49:25.920 --> 01:49:27.920
You know, who?

01:49:27.920 --> 01:49:30.960
There's the ass of people there.

01:49:30.960 --> 01:49:34.480
And most people aren't willing to take on that kind of a burden.

01:49:34.480 --> 01:49:36.400
And it's a lot of work.

01:49:36.400 --> 01:49:41.000
Well, let me ask you then, certainly fabric, because you said something earlier that really

01:49:41.000 --> 01:49:47.440
caught my attention about, you know, studying what's happened in the past and what's happening

01:49:47.440 --> 01:49:48.440
now.

01:49:48.440 --> 01:49:51.000
And then you're at the piece that you like to add to it and what should have done.

01:49:51.000 --> 01:49:52.000
Yes.

01:49:52.000 --> 01:49:57.320
So looking back on this amazing career and all of these things that you've involved in

01:49:57.320 --> 01:50:03.760
and bringing it up to the present and where we are now and what we're facing now, what

01:50:03.760 --> 01:50:05.320
should happen?

01:50:05.320 --> 01:50:10.520
The first thing is that we need to look at the past and see what happened.

01:50:10.520 --> 01:50:14.360
And then to find some lessons from that.

01:50:14.360 --> 01:50:25.080
As an example, there was a big fight amongst black members of the community throughout the

01:50:25.080 --> 01:50:33.440
country, I think, that not to follow this thing on the integration.

01:50:33.440 --> 01:50:34.440
That was necessary.

01:50:34.440 --> 01:50:36.120
It shouldn't be a thing.

01:50:36.120 --> 01:50:45.400
And as I read some time later, that core must have been after I left, but they had some

01:50:45.400 --> 01:50:55.240
in the National Committee and the National Convention about, you know, not having this

01:50:55.240 --> 01:51:05.640
is even part of the constitution and bylaws of having this thing about integration.

01:51:05.640 --> 01:51:12.520
Well, some people felt that that was the way to solve this problem, of course, and to

01:51:12.520 --> 01:51:17.120
go through the others felt that that wasn't the way.

01:51:17.120 --> 01:51:23.320
So I think we need to learn the lessons back then.

01:51:23.320 --> 01:51:28.240
And we need to learn lessons about what happened.

01:51:28.240 --> 01:51:35.200
I mean, and that's what I'm hoping to get a book written to kind of show as you've been

01:51:35.200 --> 01:51:36.720
asking me these questions.

01:51:36.720 --> 01:51:45.720
How do you get to that point where you become militant or whatever they want to call us

01:51:45.720 --> 01:51:47.400
back in those days?

01:51:47.400 --> 01:51:48.400
How do you get to that point?

01:51:48.400 --> 01:51:59.320
I was a mild matter, quiet kid, shy, who was interested in athletics and who excelled

01:51:59.320 --> 01:52:01.360
in athletics and so on.

01:52:01.360 --> 01:52:04.320
But that's what I knew.

01:52:04.320 --> 01:52:12.880
How do I get to this point where I'm willing to sacrifice my life and my career and everything

01:52:12.880 --> 01:52:14.360
else to this point?

01:52:14.360 --> 01:52:19.440
I wasn't crazy and not insane.

01:52:19.440 --> 01:52:21.920
So I hope to address that.

01:52:21.920 --> 01:52:28.440
And then to get into the future and say, okay, what are we doing now?

01:52:28.440 --> 01:52:31.560
We had the civil rights movement.

01:52:31.560 --> 01:52:39.640
We had all the past of slavery and post-slavery and leading up to the civil rights movement.

01:52:39.640 --> 01:52:42.040
We had the civil rights movement.

01:52:42.040 --> 01:52:43.920
Now what do we do?

01:52:43.920 --> 01:52:50.520
There was one area that we really haven't addressed.

01:52:50.520 --> 01:53:01.900
And the reason we didn't address it because we, including Martin Luther King and all the

01:53:01.900 --> 01:53:13.220
children of Floyd McKissie and the urban, the guy Whitney M. Young Jr and the way we didn't have

01:53:13.220 --> 01:53:24.380
the time to even think about doing anything but kicking doors open and getting jobs for

01:53:24.380 --> 01:53:30.540
our people and all this stuff and getting educated and getting into these colleges and

01:53:30.540 --> 01:53:32.180
all this stuff.

01:53:32.180 --> 01:53:41.900
But the one area that we didn't address for a number of reasons was this idea of how we

01:53:41.900 --> 01:53:52.580
fit into capitalism and how we can survive and progress under capitalism.

01:53:52.580 --> 01:53:59.100
I mean, even if you become a first class citizen, I mean, that's not enough.

01:53:59.100 --> 01:54:06.700
So I began many, many years ago to start thinking about building wealth and what that meant.

01:54:06.700 --> 01:54:13.580
And that's why I started the Black Economic Development Task Force, the Community Economic

01:54:13.580 --> 01:54:21.900
Development Group at the University and stuff like that because there's a need for us,

01:54:21.900 --> 01:54:28.540
all of us really, whites and blacks and Latinas, to really understand capitalism, how it

01:54:28.540 --> 01:54:34.340
works and what we need to do to benefit from this thing.

01:54:34.340 --> 01:54:42.060
You're not going to replace capitalism as Senator Bernie Sanders might think he can do but we'd

01:54:42.060 --> 01:54:43.060
like to do it.

01:54:43.060 --> 01:54:52.940
But we've got to understand it and then we've got to understand very strongly that capitalism

01:54:52.940 --> 01:54:57.060
wasn't just a word that was thrown up there.

01:54:57.060 --> 01:55:01.620
Capitalism means something in the first place.

01:55:01.620 --> 01:55:06.340
The word capital is very important in our economic system.

01:55:06.340 --> 01:55:09.740
That's why I called it capitalism.

01:55:09.740 --> 01:55:16.020
And so a lot of people never, when I taught the class at San Diego State in the program

01:55:16.020 --> 01:55:20.460
that I found it, they didn't really connect that.

01:55:20.460 --> 01:55:27.380
I mean, you need capital if you're really going to be successful in America.

01:55:27.380 --> 01:55:31.740
Maybe you only have a little bit of capital that comes through your savings.

01:55:31.740 --> 01:55:33.460
But you have to have some savings.

01:55:33.460 --> 01:55:38.820
You can't spend everything that comes into your household.

01:55:38.820 --> 01:55:49.900
So my thing is we've got to really focus now on educating, not just getting people

01:55:50.540 --> 01:55:56.220
and education in high school and getting there on the college.

01:55:56.220 --> 01:56:05.540
But getting them some education in this whole area of our economic system and how to survive

01:56:05.540 --> 01:56:08.340
and prosper in that.

01:56:08.340 --> 01:56:12.540
And so that's where I think we should be going.

01:56:13.540 --> 01:56:22.900
As I get into my book, I'm going to have a part of it devoted to pointing that out.

01:56:22.900 --> 01:56:24.620
This is what we should do.

01:56:24.620 --> 01:56:26.300
We haven't done it in the past.

01:56:26.300 --> 01:56:28.300
We weren't able to do it.

01:56:28.300 --> 01:56:33.900
I mean Martin Luther King has great as he was, you know, anything about economics and

01:56:33.900 --> 01:56:35.300
business and all that stuff.

01:56:35.300 --> 01:56:36.300
It wasn't his area.

01:56:36.300 --> 01:56:38.340
He was a theology.

01:56:38.340 --> 01:56:45.860
And so we really I think have got to, and that's why I started the Black Economic Development

01:56:45.860 --> 01:56:52.940
Task Force was to get us thinking about, I mean, at that time in 1987 when we started

01:56:52.940 --> 01:57:01.300
that, I mean, Black people couldn't even get that out of that Black, what?

01:57:01.300 --> 01:57:09.700
I mean, economics, I mean, they couldn't form those two words together.

01:57:09.700 --> 01:57:15.700
And so now they can because we had the program and there's been more around the country

01:57:15.700 --> 01:57:19.900
about it, but I don't hear about Black wealth.

01:57:19.900 --> 01:57:28.140
And we many of us have been taught that wealth is bad.

01:57:28.140 --> 01:57:31.260
Money, money, money, what did they say?

01:57:31.260 --> 01:57:37.620
Money, district money, corrupts, money, corrupts and all that.

01:57:37.620 --> 01:57:44.460
And until, you know, in my class and I explained how money can help, but you've got to have

01:57:44.460 --> 01:57:47.460
money to help and to survive.

01:57:47.460 --> 01:57:56.780
And the more you have through whatever profession or you decide to go into through your savings

01:57:56.780 --> 01:58:02.820
and all that, through capital, if you're in the real state development like I am, you

01:58:02.820 --> 01:58:08.820
know, you need capital, you just can't go out there and you got to purchase land and

01:58:08.820 --> 01:58:11.540
build and that takes money.

01:58:11.540 --> 01:58:19.780
And so we, one of the big things that stands in the way of that, of our getting involved

01:58:19.780 --> 01:58:28.980
in that as a Black population is that we have never learned to work together, you know,

01:58:28.980 --> 01:58:31.220
other than the church.

01:58:31.220 --> 01:58:36.180
You know, we have really, and I'm not so sure about the church.

01:58:36.180 --> 01:58:47.340
There's a lot of not getting along in the church, but we need to really focus now on that

01:58:47.340 --> 01:58:52.460
area and learn how to really be successful.

01:58:52.460 --> 01:59:01.660
And really, I mean, what I see happening now, which, which, which, you know, I hesitate

01:59:01.660 --> 01:59:05.980
to do because I'm not around the whole, I don't know what's going on around the country

01:59:05.980 --> 01:59:07.300
in that way.

01:59:07.300 --> 01:59:14.180
But what I see happening is that after the Civil Rights Movement, we hit a wall as Black

01:59:14.180 --> 01:59:15.180
people.

01:59:15.180 --> 01:59:17.900
We hit a wall and we're not doing it.

01:59:17.900 --> 01:59:20.980
We got some, some people got some jobs, good jobs.

01:59:20.980 --> 01:59:21.980
I'm one of them.

01:59:21.980 --> 01:59:23.580
You know, we got good jobs.

01:59:23.580 --> 01:59:25.780
My wife got a good job.

01:59:25.780 --> 01:59:30.220
My friends, our friends, you know, in the fraternity, they all had good jobs.

01:59:30.220 --> 01:59:38.380
But we still have so much poverty and within the Black population, we have so much lack

01:59:38.380 --> 01:59:43.140
of education within the Black population.

01:59:43.140 --> 01:59:49.940
We have so much, so many people under the criminal justice system.

01:59:49.940 --> 01:59:56.260
You know, I mean, these are all problems that we have, that we have not really found

01:59:56.260 --> 01:59:59.700
a way to address them.

01:59:59.700 --> 02:00:07.580
And usually all this stuff, education and all that stuff, you know, takes, takes money.

02:00:07.580 --> 02:00:14.740
And one of the things that we need to learn about capitalism is that, you know, capitalism

02:00:14.740 --> 02:00:17.580
exists on spending, spenders.

02:00:17.580 --> 02:00:22.540
And we've become some of the greatest spenders around.

02:00:22.540 --> 02:00:27.220
I mean, Black folks spend a lot of their money.

02:00:27.220 --> 02:00:28.220
In fact, Tony.

02:00:28.220 --> 02:00:29.220
But we become generators.

02:00:29.220 --> 02:00:30.220
That's right.

02:00:30.220 --> 02:00:32.220
They never, that's right.

02:00:32.220 --> 02:00:39.060
We're always looking for jobs, but we don't supply jobs, create jobs.

02:00:39.060 --> 02:00:42.460
And some, this is the question of what power looks like.

02:00:42.460 --> 02:00:43.460
Yeah.

02:00:43.460 --> 02:00:45.700
Or as an equation, and this is a piece of that.

02:00:45.700 --> 02:00:46.700
Yeah, exactly.

02:00:46.700 --> 02:00:50.740
And when you're talking about it, me and the conversation, I had with a long time, long,

02:00:50.740 --> 02:00:56.460
long time activists in Georgia, and I asked him, we were talking about when Black, the

02:00:56.460 --> 02:00:58.460
phrase Black power first started.

02:00:58.460 --> 02:00:59.460
Yeah.

02:00:59.460 --> 02:01:00.460
It's so clear.

02:01:00.460 --> 02:01:03.780
And he asked him what he thought, what it meant to him.

02:01:03.780 --> 02:01:05.540
And he said economic power.

02:01:05.540 --> 02:01:07.940
And some determination and economic power.

02:01:07.940 --> 02:01:08.940
Yes.

02:01:08.940 --> 02:01:09.940
That's what it's got to be.

02:01:09.940 --> 02:01:10.940
Yes.

02:01:10.940 --> 02:01:12.940
I'm reminded of that when you were in the middle of it.

02:01:12.940 --> 02:01:13.940
Yes.

02:01:13.940 --> 02:01:16.820
You reminded me just now the term self-determination.

02:01:16.820 --> 02:01:23.420
That was something that was very strong within me.

02:01:23.420 --> 02:01:33.180
It just motivated me so much because I could see one day where we would have things in

02:01:33.180 --> 02:01:36.900
our hands where we could determine for ourselves what we wanted to do.

02:01:36.900 --> 02:01:43.900
And I think that was one of the problems with me, with the the peace movement and the trotsky

02:01:43.900 --> 02:01:47.420
IH's and communists and all that stuff.

02:01:47.420 --> 02:01:50.580
I mean, first of all, they were all white.

02:01:50.580 --> 02:01:53.580
And then all blacks involved in that.

02:01:53.580 --> 02:02:02.300
And secondly, they wanted to impose their will on core.

02:02:02.300 --> 02:02:10.540
And I mean, I was just dead set against that because I was very, very interested in

02:02:10.540 --> 02:02:13.660
surn with self-determination.

02:02:13.660 --> 02:02:18.860
And I used that term in med meetings in core.

02:02:18.860 --> 02:02:22.460
But that's where I see us going.

02:02:22.460 --> 02:02:27.300
But you know, there has to be an example.

02:02:27.300 --> 02:02:36.420
And so when I left retired from San Diego State, I set out to make an example of how it

02:02:36.420 --> 02:02:38.540
can be done.

02:02:38.540 --> 02:02:43.180
And that's why I'm in real estate and land development now.

02:02:43.180 --> 02:02:48.500
And I'm with a couple partners and so forth.

02:02:48.500 --> 02:02:51.860
I think they have to see it happen.

02:02:51.860 --> 02:03:00.860
And they have to see it happen not by an athlete, not by someone who broke into the movies,

02:03:00.860 --> 02:03:02.420
the movie star.

02:03:02.420 --> 02:03:14.980
You know, at least they see it happening with one of the block blocking, you know, these

02:03:14.980 --> 02:03:22.060
the guy in the music industry, these guys, rap, rap guys, you know, see it happening?

02:03:22.060 --> 02:03:24.020
Few, you know.

02:03:24.020 --> 02:03:33.380
But we've got to find a way to show our kids that, you know, say, oh, how brown, Mr.

02:03:33.380 --> 02:03:37.740
Brown is a millionaire.

02:03:37.740 --> 02:03:42.060
He is, yeah.

02:03:42.060 --> 02:03:49.060
Who he played for?

02:03:49.060 --> 02:03:51.060
Exactly.

02:03:51.060 --> 02:03:52.060
Exactly.

02:03:52.060 --> 02:03:56.380
And they've got to see examples of that.

02:03:56.380 --> 02:04:06.340
Our son who played basketball for Stanford, he, the coach, I guess, had them going out

02:04:06.340 --> 02:04:10.340
in the community and talking to kids and so forth.

02:04:10.340 --> 02:04:20.180
So our son told us, and they said he went out to talk to a group of kids and he was

02:04:20.180 --> 02:04:25.580
unprepared to talk with them about school and things like that.

02:04:25.580 --> 02:04:31.740
And before he could really, your son said, you're kids right at the hands.

02:04:31.740 --> 02:04:32.980
How much your shoes cost?

02:04:33.780 --> 02:04:38.100
You know, tennis shoes, you know.

02:04:38.100 --> 02:04:41.700
What kind of car do you drive?

02:04:41.700 --> 02:04:43.980
This went on and on like that.

02:04:43.980 --> 02:04:46.580
It was so frustrating for him.

02:04:46.580 --> 02:04:51.380
I mean, it's the mist, the mark so much, you know.

02:04:51.380 --> 02:04:57.460
And that's what, I mean, what surprises me though, is that so much of that still exists

02:04:57.460 --> 02:05:00.180
to this day.

02:05:00.180 --> 02:05:03.220
And I go around and meet my fraternity and so forth.

02:05:03.220 --> 02:05:09.420
I mean, you know, doctors, lawyers, businessmen, educators, all in high positions.

02:05:09.420 --> 02:05:20.260
We all had great positions, but no education really in business, economics, and that sort

02:05:20.260 --> 02:05:22.100
of thing.

02:05:22.100 --> 02:05:33.340
So the medicine, a lot of doctors, not in and so, but I just think that's the next step.

02:05:33.340 --> 02:05:48.780
And I said this back in about 1980s and I wrote, we used to have black economic summits.

02:05:48.780 --> 02:05:57.300
That was my idea, you know, to bring people together and talk about economics.

02:05:57.300 --> 02:06:00.860
And we did that for several years.

02:06:00.860 --> 02:06:12.380
And in our program, we would always have something from me in front of the program.

02:06:12.380 --> 02:06:25.980
And I remember talking about, you know, what we should be doing and bringing about a

02:06:25.980 --> 02:06:39.300
real consciousness of making economics apart, should be the next step.

02:06:39.300 --> 02:06:45.540
That's what I used with the next step of the civil rights movement, should be in economic

02:06:45.540 --> 02:06:48.140
development.

02:06:48.140 --> 02:06:51.860
Well, I thought it was going to take off around the country.

02:06:51.860 --> 02:06:58.260
You know, I thought I saw signs of things happening and so forth, but not really.

02:06:58.260 --> 02:07:02.980
I think, you know, we hit a wall.

02:07:02.980 --> 02:07:12.540
And as an example, here in San Diego, and I must admit, I just don't have a feel for

02:07:12.540 --> 02:07:16.900
what's going on around the country and the communities and so forth.

02:07:16.900 --> 02:07:20.660
I know it's going on politically.

02:07:20.660 --> 02:07:31.500
But we just, you know, I see a wall and we haven't really, I mean, we've gotten some jobs

02:07:31.580 --> 02:07:36.340
as I said earlier, but you know, that's it.

02:07:36.340 --> 02:07:43.860
San Diego, when core days, when we had core, we had a voice.

02:07:43.860 --> 02:07:53.060
The city fathers and so forth, you know, when things came up, as other guys, core came

02:07:53.060 --> 02:07:55.620
to mind.

02:07:55.620 --> 02:07:57.820
We don't have a voice now.

02:07:57.820 --> 02:08:02.060
I just met with the, well, it's met.

02:08:02.060 --> 02:08:15.540
I've been talking with the, the President, CEO of San Diego, Urban League and he wanted

02:08:15.540 --> 02:08:20.660
to know, you know, get my thoughts and things on how the Urban League could become more

02:08:20.660 --> 02:08:22.660
effective and so on.

02:08:22.660 --> 02:08:30.980
So we've been meeting so forth and I put together a group of guys to, as kind of a think tank

02:08:30.980 --> 02:08:33.460
to just sit around and talk with him and so forth.

02:08:33.460 --> 02:08:38.100
And we did that one Saturday and we'd probably do it again.

02:08:38.100 --> 02:08:45.460
But someone has to kind of take the lead, you know, and not only in the African American

02:08:45.460 --> 02:08:49.940
community, but I mean, it's the same applies for the Latino community, same as the Filipino

02:08:49.940 --> 02:08:51.460
community and the same.

02:08:51.460 --> 02:08:53.460
You know, with the Asian.

02:08:53.460 --> 02:08:58.460
Yeah, I mean, and do you see some potential because some, you know, especially with, you're

02:08:58.460 --> 02:09:02.860
giving an example of core and some of the groups that, sometimes it's the seed of anger

02:09:02.860 --> 02:09:04.860
that, or, you know, that motivation.

02:09:04.860 --> 02:09:05.860
Yeah, absolutely.

02:09:05.860 --> 02:09:09.900
So do you see any potential then, you know, with what we see, we'll solve it with the

02:09:09.900 --> 02:09:15.100
Black Lives Matter or with the folks who are following Senator Bernie Sanders, they've talked

02:09:15.100 --> 02:09:16.100
about.

02:09:16.100 --> 02:09:23.380
Do you see any of that emotional, whatever is driving those movements that gives you

02:09:23.380 --> 02:09:25.300
some hope at all?

02:09:25.300 --> 02:09:26.820
Unfortunately, no.

02:09:26.820 --> 02:09:32.340
You know, I don't, and you're absolutely right and we've said that, you know, years back,

02:09:32.340 --> 02:09:39.140
you know, there's got to be some anger, you know, or you don't get anything done.

02:09:39.140 --> 02:09:45.620
Somebody has to do something to cause a lot of commotion and then you will get people's

02:09:45.620 --> 02:09:46.620
attention.

02:09:46.620 --> 02:09:55.820
But, without that, you know, so the only place that I know of where it can be done is,

02:09:55.820 --> 02:10:00.740
it has to be forced on them in the schools.

02:10:00.740 --> 02:10:08.380
And I thought the Black Studies programs around the country would do that, but I mean, I don't

02:10:08.380 --> 02:10:11.300
see any signs of their annoying.

02:10:11.300 --> 02:10:19.340
I mean, talking about your project here, I mean, the need for it is so great because people

02:10:19.340 --> 02:10:22.660
don't even know about it.

02:10:22.660 --> 02:10:28.500
People in my age group here in San Diego, you just say something about the Civil Rights

02:10:28.500 --> 02:10:30.620
Movement in San Diego, they go, what?

02:10:30.620 --> 02:10:31.620
I don't know.

02:10:31.620 --> 02:10:36.420
There was a Civil Rights Movement in San Diego.

02:10:36.420 --> 02:10:43.420
And those are the people in, you know, my age group should have known about it, much

02:10:43.420 --> 02:10:47.740
not, much less than participating in it, they should have really known about it, but

02:10:47.740 --> 02:10:50.060
then they've been not a younger people.

02:10:50.060 --> 02:10:53.420
They have no idea.

02:10:53.420 --> 02:11:01.660
I can remember speaking to a class at San Diego State when we formed the Black, when we formed

02:11:01.660 --> 02:11:12.700
the African American Studies program, it must have been 1972.

02:11:12.700 --> 02:11:17.500
And I was asked by one of the faculty members that I hired to come around and speak to

02:11:17.500 --> 02:11:24.980
this group about her class about the Civil Rights Movement and I went in there, none of

02:11:24.980 --> 02:11:25.980
them knew anything.

02:11:25.980 --> 02:11:30.780
Now that was back then.

02:11:30.780 --> 02:11:36.020
So we really have a problem, I think.

02:11:36.020 --> 02:11:46.700
I don't know how else we can do it unless it's force fed through the schools that people,

02:11:46.700 --> 02:11:55.260
well, my goal, one of my goals was in the African American Studies program that I got organized

02:11:55.260 --> 02:12:09.540
at San Diego State was to eventually market it, market it to the total university.

02:12:09.540 --> 02:12:17.140
I mean because that had just made sense to me, it just can't be for Black students.

02:12:17.140 --> 02:12:25.980
And so I sort of got ousted a little bit because of some more internal things.

02:12:25.980 --> 02:12:26.980
I don't know.

02:12:26.980 --> 02:12:34.100
I wish to write people around the country who were much more involved than I and so forth.

02:12:34.100 --> 02:12:38.140
They could write about this internal stuff that happens.

02:12:38.140 --> 02:12:49.420
I bet you Reverend Jesse L. Jackson Sr could write a whole lot about it and it's got started this,

02:12:49.420 --> 02:13:01.700
who got involved with starting this project at the Charles, I mean Lewis, John, John.

02:13:01.700 --> 02:13:06.780
I bet you they could tell you a whole lot of stories about the infighting and stuff that

02:13:06.780 --> 02:13:18.860
went on that sort of kept the progress from being more than it was.

02:13:18.860 --> 02:13:23.220
So I'll tell you, we're still having the same fights and conversations that we were saying

02:13:23.220 --> 02:13:29.580
about it shouldn't, Black studies shouldn't just be over here stuck in its corner.

02:13:29.580 --> 02:13:33.380
These are classes that should be in the general curriculum.

02:13:33.380 --> 02:13:37.740
Absolutely.

02:13:37.740 --> 02:13:47.860
You know I'm much older now more tired, better known as worn out.

02:13:47.860 --> 02:13:50.980
Where is you?

02:13:50.980 --> 02:13:57.900
Honestly, when I finished the Civil Rights Movement, I mean I didn't know what was going on

02:13:57.900 --> 02:13:58.900
at the time.

02:13:58.900 --> 02:14:03.340
My left core, I mean my nervous system was shot.

02:14:03.340 --> 02:14:09.860
I couldn't sit at a meeting or talk to people about it.

02:14:09.860 --> 02:14:13.780
I couldn't even, my nervous system was completely shot.

02:14:13.780 --> 02:14:21.460
I didn't realize what was going on but that was close to a nervous breakdown.

02:14:21.460 --> 02:14:23.460
So not uncommon.

02:14:23.460 --> 02:14:26.260
I don't know how to talk to other activists.

02:14:26.260 --> 02:14:27.260
Absolutely.

02:14:27.260 --> 02:14:29.500
I'm a bit sad.

02:14:29.500 --> 02:14:30.500
High stress.

02:14:30.500 --> 02:14:31.500
Yeah, high stress.

02:14:31.500 --> 02:14:35.020
Almost dramatic stress in some cases.

02:14:35.020 --> 02:14:37.420
You're the first person.

02:14:37.420 --> 02:14:42.460
I've thought about that a lot and I've said it to my wife.

02:14:42.460 --> 02:14:50.940
But you know, I mean I don't sleep well and I play back a lot of stuff over all those

02:14:50.940 --> 02:14:53.740
years and they hit me one time.

02:14:53.740 --> 02:14:57.580
You know, I mean that's what they're talking about, about people coming back from the

02:14:57.580 --> 02:15:01.300
wars and stuff, post-traumatic stress.

02:15:01.300 --> 02:15:02.300
Same stuff.

02:15:02.300 --> 02:15:06.220
Absolutely the same stuff.

02:15:06.220 --> 02:15:09.860
And I think it's just beginnings, some of the activists are just beginning to recognize

02:15:09.860 --> 02:15:11.860
that they're sad.

02:15:11.860 --> 02:15:18.580
And there are some activists who tore them apart early on, and they ended up strong out

02:15:18.580 --> 02:15:19.580
on drugs.

02:15:19.580 --> 02:15:23.020
Yeah, they couldn't deal with that.

02:15:23.020 --> 02:15:36.820
I think that's where we need to go.

02:15:36.820 --> 02:15:39.020
That's part of the answer anyhow.

02:15:39.020 --> 02:15:45.580
I think that we've got to really get economic minded.

02:15:45.580 --> 02:15:56.340
And we've got to, do you remember last name was Brown.

02:15:56.340 --> 02:15:58.340
I'm having trouble.

02:15:58.340 --> 02:16:00.980
I'm wearing you out, right?

02:16:00.980 --> 02:16:03.100
Tony, Tony Brown?

02:16:03.100 --> 02:16:05.380
You know about Tony Brown?

02:16:05.380 --> 02:16:13.660
Tony Brown had a program on KPBS for some years.

02:16:13.660 --> 02:16:23.540
And his focus was on economics, black businesses and all this stuff.

02:16:23.540 --> 02:16:42.220
And I have a video tape that he put together showing how black spending and how blacks only

02:16:42.220 --> 02:16:47.780
spent 1% or less in those black communities.

02:16:47.780 --> 02:16:53.340
And he's talking about back years and years.

02:16:53.340 --> 02:16:55.460
But Tony, I don't know what happened to him.

02:16:55.460 --> 02:16:57.700
I don't think he died.

02:16:57.700 --> 02:17:00.780
But he sort of disappeared.

02:17:00.780 --> 02:17:05.340
He put out a movie called Weight Girl.

02:17:05.340 --> 02:17:08.100
Weight Girl is in what you think he's talking about.

02:17:08.100 --> 02:17:14.180
He's talking about the drugs that was called Weight Girl.

02:17:14.180 --> 02:17:20.940
And he put out that movie and I helped him to get it out here in San Diego and stuff.

02:17:20.940 --> 02:17:33.980
But Tony was very active in this area of building black businesses and creating wealth among

02:17:33.980 --> 02:17:34.980
him.

02:17:34.980 --> 02:17:36.660
He used the word wealth so much.

02:17:36.660 --> 02:17:42.060
But that's what he was talking about doing that.

02:17:42.060 --> 02:17:54.540
So maybe, you know, if we had somebody like on the level of Representative John Lewis in Congress, which

02:17:54.540 --> 02:18:04.260
reminds me, I don't know why we don't get this kind of a message from the black business.

02:18:04.260 --> 02:18:11.260
I don't know why we don't get this message.

02:18:11.260 --> 02:18:14.900
I don't see any leadership coming from them.

02:18:14.900 --> 02:18:16.860
Although I like them.

02:18:16.860 --> 02:18:21.060
I love them because they're in these positions and stuff.

02:18:21.060 --> 02:18:23.740
But I don't see any real leadership coming.

02:18:23.740 --> 02:18:35.820
And Reverend Jesse L. Jackson Sr disappeared and then we have Reverend Al Sharpton at him.

02:18:35.820 --> 02:18:41.900
But I remember Jesse used to come out here in San Diego many, many years ago.

02:18:41.900 --> 02:18:46.900
He would be talking and talking and talking about him and treating all this stuff.

02:18:46.900 --> 02:18:52.740
But never, nothing, not a word about the importance of economics.

02:18:52.740 --> 02:18:56.580
I remember saying that back in those years.

02:18:56.580 --> 02:19:04.340
Well, we don't have anybody in leadership positions to speak to that.

02:19:04.340 --> 02:19:10.820
If I could get my hands on Hillary Rodham Clinton, I would twist her arm.

02:19:10.820 --> 02:19:13.220
Hillary Rodham Clinton, I would make a $5 donation.

02:19:13.220 --> 02:19:14.220
Now listen.

02:19:14.220 --> 02:19:17.220
I'm sure it brings you five.

02:19:17.220 --> 02:19:19.220
Yeah, it brings you close.

02:19:19.220 --> 02:19:20.220
She got a website.

02:19:20.220 --> 02:19:21.220
I understand.

02:19:21.220 --> 02:19:22.220
You're from?

02:19:22.220 --> 02:19:28.220
Well, she ever, you know, where does that go?

02:19:28.220 --> 02:19:30.220
Oh, well.

02:19:30.220 --> 02:19:31.220
Interesting world.

02:19:31.220 --> 02:19:32.220
Yeah.

02:19:32.220 --> 02:19:34.340
Very interesting.

02:19:34.340 --> 02:19:39.420
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum

02:19:39.420 --> 02:19:41.900
of African American History and Culture.

